# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chicago-tribune
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chicago-tribune/1819-news] The name *1819 News* is a reference to the year that the state of Alabama was admitted to the union.
[src:chicago-tribune/1819-news] The website became fully independent of the Alabama Policy Institute with the two organizations officially dissociating on December 31, 2022, followed by an announcement of *1819 News*'s independence in January 2023.
[src:chicago-tribune/1819-news] *1819 News* is now managed by a non-profit LLC of the same name.
[src:chicago-tribune/1819-news] In February 2023, YouTube suspended the account of *1819 News: The Podcast* for violating the website's community guidelines; *1819 News* characterized the suspension as "Big Tech censorship" in a follow-up article.
[src:chicago-tribune/1819-news] In December 2022, *1819 News* published a series of articles reporting on the financial connections of former Republican Alabama House of Representatives speaker Mac McCutcheon, including McCutcheon's links to convicted fraudster John Hornbuckle.
[src:chicago-tribune/1819-news] In February 2023, *1819 News* first reported on leaked recordings of Montgomery mayor Steven Reed making profanity-laden comments about Maxwell Air Force Base.
[src:chicago-tribune/1819-news] In November 2023, *1819 News* published an article on Bubba Copeland, a Baptist minister and the mayor of Smiths Station, Alabama.
[src:chicago-tribune/1819-news] The piece included social media posts from Copeland, under a pseudonym, in which he cross-dressed wearing women's clothing and described himself as a "transgender curvy girl".
[src:chicago-tribune/1819-news] *1819 News* also released a follow-up article stating that Copeland had written a violent fictional story featuring a real-life woman and posted pictures of local residents, including minors, without their knowledge; the follow-up article was noted in reporting on the situation by *NBC News*.
[src:chicago-tribune/1819-news] Copeland died by suicide on November 3, 2023, two days after the articles were published.
[src:chicago-tribune/1819-news] Copeland's suicide received national attention and drew criticism to *1819 News* from national and local figures.
[src:chicago-tribune/1819-news] Lee County Democratic Party chair Jamie Lowe condemned "the use of discriminatory and hateful rhetoric to target the personal lives of individuals".
[src:chicago-tribune/1819-news] Doug Jones, a former U.S. senator from Alabama, described the website's treatment of Copeland as "sad and disgusting".
[src:chicago-tribune/1819-news] Fogel was subsequently hired by *1819 News* and has served as a commentator there since May 2024.
[src:chicago-tribune/1819-news] The articles reportedly prompted a response from university president Beck A.
[src:chicago-tribune/1819-news] Taylor; Fogel claimed that Taylor called the *1819 News* stories "unfair, out of context, and at times completely false" in an email to the university's board of trustees.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The **2013 Stanley Cup Final** was the championship series of the National Hockey League's (NHL) 2012–13 season, and the conclusion of the 2013 Stanley Cup playoffs.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The Western Conference playoff champion Chicago Blackhawks defeated the Eastern Conference playoff champion Boston Bruins in six games to win their fifth Stanley Cup in team history.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The Blackhawks also became just the eighth team to win both the Cup and the Presidents' Trophy (as the team with the best regular season record) in the same season.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] To date, they are the last team to win these two trophies in the same season.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Chicago's Patrick Kane was awarded the Conn Smythe Trophy as the Most Valuable Player of the playoffs.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Due to a lockout that both shortened and delayed the start of the regular season, the 2013 Cup Finals began on June 12, and lasted until June 24–tying the lockout impacted 1995 and 2024 for the latest in June that the Stanley Cup was awarded.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] This was the first Stanley Cup Final series between two Original Six teams since 1979, and the seventh since its first expansion in 1967.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] It also marked the first time these two teams have met in the Stanley Cup Final.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] In Game 6, while trailing the Bruins 2–1 with 76 seconds left in the third period, Chicago's Bryan Bickell and Dave Bolland scored two goals in 17 seconds to win the Cup for the Blackhawks.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The win was the Blackhawks' second in four years, after also claiming the title in 2010.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] It was the first Finals series since 2004 to be tied after two games.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] It was also the first Stanley Cup Final since 1993 to feature three overtime games, including the fifth longest game in Finals history.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] This series is the last time to date that a Presidents' Trophy winner has won the Stanley Cup.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] This was the first meeting between teams from Boston and Chicago for a major professional sports championship since Super Bowl XX in 1986, which featured the Chicago Bears and New England Patriots.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] This was the Boston Bruins's nineteenth appearance in the Stanley Cup Final, a couple years removed from 2011, when they also faced the Presidents' Trophy winners, the Vancouver Canucks whom they defeated to win their sixth Cup championship.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The Bruins entered the season without the services of goalie Tim Thomas, the Conn Smythe Trophy winner during Boston's 2011 championship.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] It was announced on June 3, 2012, that he planned on taking a year off from hockey.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Thomas was eventually traded to the New York Islanders on February 7, 2013.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Tuukka Rask succeeded Thomas as the Bruins' starting goalie.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Another of the Bruins' major trades was sending Benoit Pouliot to the Tampa Bay Lightning.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Then on April 2, 2013, with about a month left in the lockout-shortened regular season, Boston acquired veteran Jaromir Jagr from the Dallas Stars.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Boston finished the lockout-shortened regular season with 62 points, finishing in second place in the Northeast Division, and the fourth seed in the Eastern Conference.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Throughout the regular season, the Bruins and the Montreal Canadiens were neck-and-neck in the division, but the Bruins lost their last game to the Ottawa Senators, a contest that was postponed until the end of the regular season due to the Boston Marathon bombing.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] In the first round of the playoffs, Boston rallied from a 4–1 third period deficit in Game 7 to defeat the Toronto Maple Leafs in overtime.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The Bruins then eliminated the New York Rangers in five games, and then swept the top seeded Pittsburgh Penguins in the Eastern Conference Final.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] This was the Chicago Blackhawks' twelfth appearance in the Stanley Cup Final.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The Blackhawks sought their fifth Cup championship overall and their first since 2010.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] In both 2011 and 2012, the Blackhawks were eliminated in the first round of the playoffs by the Presidents' Trophy-winning Canucks and Phoenix Coyotes, respectively.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The Blackhawks began the lockout-shortened regular season by setting the NHL record for most games to start a season without a regulation loss (24), recording their first regulation loss in their 25th game of the season: a 6–2 defeat to the Colorado Avalanche.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The Blackhawks finished the regular season with an NHL-best 77 points, winning their second Presidents' Trophy in team history.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] In the first round of the playoffs, the Blackhawks defeated the Minnesota Wild in five games.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] In the next round, Chicago came back from a 3–1 series deficit to defeat the Detroit Red Wings in overtime of Game 7.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] In the Western Conference Final, the Blackhawks defeated the defending Stanley Cup champion Los Angeles Kings in five games.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The Blackhawks rallied from a 3–1 third period deficit in game one to defeat the Bruins in triple-overtime, 4–3.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] This was the 24th longest NHL overtime game, and the fifth longest in the history of the Stanley Cup Final.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Milan Lucic scored at 13:11 of the first period and 51 seconds into the second period to give the Bruins a 2–0 lead.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] At 3:08 of the second period, Chicago rookie Brandon Saad scored his first career playoff goal, ending Boston goalie Tuukka Rask's shutout streak of 149:36, and cutting Boston's lead to 2–1.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Chicago then had a 5-on-3 for 1:17 midway through the second period, but could not get a shot on goal.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The Bruins then increased their lead to 3–1 when Patrice Bergeron scored a power-play goal at 06:09 of the third period.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] But Dave Bolland and Johnny Oduya scored in 4:14 apart to tie the game.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] In the overtime periods, the Blackhawks were penalized twice for too many men on the ice, but Boston was unable to score on those two ensuing power-plays.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The game finally ended at 12:08 of the third overtime period when Michal Rozsival's shot from the point deflected off of Bolland, then Andrew Shaw, and past Rask into the Boston net.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The Bruins tied the series with a 2–1 overtime victory in game two.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] This was the third consecutive overtime game for the Blackhawks (dating back to the conference finals), and the second consecutive Cup Finals in which the first two games went into overtime.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] In the first period, Chicago had 19 shots on goal compared to Boston's 4, but only scored on Patrick Sharp's goal at 11:22.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Seventy seconds later, a goal by the Blackhawks' Marian Hossa was disallowed after officials blew the play dead prior to the puck crossing the Bruins' goal line.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Boston's Chris Kelly then scored his first goal of the playoffs at 14:58 of the second period to tie the game.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Boston goalie Tuukka Rask stopped all 28 Chicago shots in the Bruins' 2–0 victory in game three.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Daniel Paille scored Boston's first goal at 02:13 of the second period.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Patrice Bergeron then scored a power play goal at 14:05 of the second period, just seconds after the Bruins' 5-on-3 advantage expired.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The Blackhawks' Marian Hossa was scratched from the game; Chicago head coach Joel Quenneville later said after the game that Hossa did not play due to an upper-body injury.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] After only 12 total goals were scored in the first three games, game four featured a series high 11 total goals.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] In the first period, Chicago's Michal Handzus scored a short-handed goal at 06:48 before Boston's Rich Peverley tied the game on a power play goal at 14:43.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Five total goals were then scored in the second period.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Jonathan Toews deflected Michal Rozsival's shot into the Boston net at 6:48 to give the Blackhawks a 2–1 lead.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Chicago then scored again at 8:41: Bryan Bickell's shot was stopped by Tuukka Rask, but Patrick Kane grabbed the rebound from the other side and shot it into the net before the Boston goalie could recover.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Milan Lucic cut the lead, 3–2, at 14:43 after shooting a rebound past Chicago goalie Corey Crawford, but Chicago scored right back at 15:32 with Marcus Kruger's goal on a 2-on-1 breakaway.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] At 17:22, the Bruins scored their second power play goal after Zdeno Chara's shot deflected over the net, hit the glass, then eventually bounced into the crease where Patrice Bergeron tapped it into the net before Crawford could find the puck.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] In the third period, Bergeron tied the game, 4–4, at 2:05.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The Blackhawks then scored their first power play goal of the series with Patrick Sharp's score at 11:19, but Boston answered 55 seconds later with Johnny Boychuk's equalizer.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] At 09:51 of overtime, Brent Seabrook scored from the point through traffic to give the Blackhawks a 6–5 victory in game four to even the series at 2.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] All five Bruins goals were shot to the glove side of Crawford, but the Blackhawks never once trailed in this game.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Patrick Kane scored two goals in the Blackhawks' 3–1 victory in game five.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Chicago built a 2–0 lead with Kane's goals at 17:27 of the first period and 05:13 of the second.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Boston's Zdeno Chara cut the score to 2–1 at 03:40 of the third period, but Chicago goalie Corey Crawford stopped 24 of 25 Bruins shots, and Dave Bolland added an empty net goal in the waning seconds of the game.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Boston's Patrice Bergeron left the game in the second period and was later taken to the hospital for observation, while Chicago's Jonathan Toews suffered an upper body injury and did not play in the third period.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] With Chicago holding a 3–2 series lead heading into game six, the desperate Bruins outshot the Blackhawks 12–6 in the first period, with the Bruins ending the period up 1–0 due to Chris Kelly's goal.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] However, Chicago would fight back in the second period, as Blackhawks captain Jonathan Toews scored on a breakaway while shorthanded to tie the game (Toews' goal would be recorded as an even strength goal, as it entered the net just after Andrew Shaw's penalty expired).
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The teams entered the third period with the game tied 1–1.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] However, Milan Lucic would score at 12:11 of the third period to put the Bruins in front again.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] With the Bruins clinging onto a 2–1 lead late in the third period, the Blackhawks pulled goalie Corey Crawford for the extra attacker.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] This resulted in Bryan Bickell scoring the game-tying goal with 76 seconds remaining in the game on a feed from Jonathan Toews.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Thus, with the score tied 2–2, it appeared the Finals would go to overtime for the fourth time.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] However, only 17 seconds after Bickell's goal, Dave Bolland scored what proved to be the series-winning goal, as the Bruins were unable to get an equalizer in the final minute with goalie Tuukka Rask on the bench.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Bolland's goal at 19:01 of the third period broke the record for the latest Stanley Cup game-winner scored in regulation.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] In Canada, the series was televised in English on CBC and in French on the cable network RDS.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The NBC Sports Group's coverage in the United States was different from previous seasons: the NBC broadcast network televised game one and then the final four games, while the NBC Sports Network broadcast games two and three.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] Years indicated in **boldface** under the "Finals appearance" column signify that the player won the Stanley Cup in the given year.
[src:chicago-tribune/2013-stanley-cup-finals] The 2013 Stanley Cup was presented to Blackhawks captain Jonathan Toews by NHL Commissioner Gary Bettman, following the Blackhawks' 3–2 win over the Bruins in the sixth game of the finals.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] Prior to 1963, Phyllis Schlafly had prepared a whole series of Republican speeches that she hoped to deliver.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] However, after the assassination of John F.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] Kennedy, she deemed it inappropriate to give anti-Democratic speeches.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] Schlafly hoped to have a permanent effect so she converted this speech into a book, which became *A Choice Not an Echo*.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] By establishing her own publisher, the Pere Marquette Press, Schlafly was able to quickly self-publish her book, which she distributed in mass quantities.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] By the weekend after publication, Schlafly's book had statewide distribution in California and eventually had sold over half a million copies by May of that year, helping to support Goldwater's campaign.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] Throughout the 1940s, 50s, and 60s, Democrats maintained control of the executive office, with the exception of the 1953–1961 Eisenhower presidency.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] The Republican party had often been split between a conservative wing supported in the Midwest and West, and liberal wing from the Northeast.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] The conservative wing, which Schlafly was a part of, opposed New Deal reforms and supported isolationist policies.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] This wing was represented by candidates such as Robert A.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] On the other side, the liberal wing of the Republican party demanded more efficient use of New Deal policies and were led by Thomas E.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] Dewey, who Schlafly claims was subject to the will of the kingmakers.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] The liberal wing maintained control of the Republican Presidential nomination until 1964.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] In 1964, the conservative wing made a comeback against the liberal wing by nominating Barry Goldwater.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] Goldwater defeated Nelson Rockefeller and Henry Cabot Lodge Jr., who were on the left side of the GOP.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] However, Goldwater was defeated by Johnson in the 1964 election.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] Phyllis Schlafly's *A Choice Not an Echo* was a key factor in Barry Goldwater's securing of the 1964 Republican nomination.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] In preceding months, Goldwater was close to winning the nomination, but needed to win a major primary in order to do so.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] The California primary, therefore, was key if Goldwater were to win the Republican nomination.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] The liberal New York governor Nelson Rockefeller opposed Goldwater in the California primary.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] Conservative lobbyists and volunteers traveled to various precincts and handed out copies of *A Choice Not an Echo*.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] Schlafly's book was evidently very influential: later studies showed that Goldwater had secured narrow victories in many of these precincts.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] Goldwater won the California primary, and got the Republican presidential nomination.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] The first appearance of the "kingmakers" is in Chapter 5.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] "The Advertising Agent's Holiday" describes how Wendell Willkie, who was a registered Democrat, was marketed into becoming the 1940 Republican presidential candidate by the kingmakers, who were very prominent business and economic figures during the time.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] Willkie began appearing on the covers of magazines and newspapers, and was placed on panels where the questions were tailored specifically to his knowledge.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] This type of marketing ensured that he appeared to outsmart other intellectuals on the panels.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] Despite this marketing, when the Republican National Convention was seven weeks away, Willkie was only favored by 3% of Republicans.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] When the Republican National Convention arrived, the kingmakers launched "Operation Telegram".
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] In this operation, prominent and financially powerful people were called and asked if they would like to send a telegram to the delegates at the Republican National Convention on their behalf.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] As a result of this, almost a million telegrams flooded the delegates at the convention in favor of Willkie.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] In addition, cab drivers picking up delegates and taking them to the convention were paid to hint that the nomination was leaning towards Willkie.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] The combination of these strategies worked, and Willkie won the presidential nomination, with Taft and Dewey trailing behind.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] Chapter 12 of *A Choice Not an Echo* is titled "Anybody but Goldwater".
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] In this chapter of her book, Schlafly focuses in on the work of the kingmakers' attempts to prevent Goldwater from securing the Republican popular vote.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] The members of that elite will not lightly relinquish their party to Barry Goldwater.'" Schlafly also references other magazines that have published "anti-Goldwater" texts such as *The New Yorker* and *The Saturday Evening Post*.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] More specifically, Schlafly references an article published in *The Saturday Evening Post* on January 25, 1964 called "How the Republicans Can Win" by Arthur Larson, that advises the GOP to select a candidate who appeals to the "Authentic American Center" (specifically referencing John F.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] Aside from "anti-Goldwater propaganda", Schlafly reveals other strategies used by the kingmakers to keep Goldwater out of the race.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] Scranton, who was Governor of Pennsylvania from 1963–1967.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] The kingmakers invested a lot of attention in Governor Scranton, "showing off Scranton to leading banking, industrial and communications figures in a series of private luncheons." These exclusive meetings included extremely influential individuals who would help bolster Scranton's campaign.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] The book helped create space within the Republican Party for the modern conservative movement that eventually stopped the passage of the Equal Rights Amendment in the 1970s.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] It called on conservatives to rally against the liberal wing and offer a true conservative for the nomination.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] Millions of copies of this book were bought and distributed by supporters of Goldwater, making it one of the all-time best selling conservative political books in the United States.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] The book helped launch the career of Phyllis Schlafly as a movement conservative.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] The 50th anniversary edition, *A Choice Not an Echo: Updated and Expanded 50th Anniversary Edition*, was published in 2014 by Regnery Publishing, ISBN 978-1621573159.
[src:chicago-tribune/a-choice-not-an-echo] The 1964 book was published by the Pere Marquette Press, and has the ISBN ISBN 0-686-11486-8.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] ABC Radio aired the first broadcast report of the assassination of President John F.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Kennedy was shot in Dallas, Texas, at 18:30 UTC and Don Gardiner anchored the initial bulletin at 18:36:50 UTC, minutes before any other radio or television network.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Beginning in the late 1950s, ABC fed hourly newscasts to affiliates at 5 minutes before the hour, to contrast it with CBS Radio News and NBC Radio News, which sent its newscasts to affiliates at the top of each hour.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] On January 1, 1968, the singular ABC radio network was split into 4 separate and distinct programming services.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] The *American Contemporary Network*, on major-market contemporary music stations like WABC New York, aired news at 5 minutes before the hour.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] *American Information Network* news ran at the top of the hour on major-market talk and information stations like KGO San Francisco.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Before the split, ABC reached an understanding with the FCC concerning the "Chain Broadcasting" rule, which forced the sale of the NBC Blue Network and enabled ABC's creation in 1943.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Each of the four networks could be cleared only when no other ABC network was on the air in a particular market.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Though each of the 4 new "networks" were distributed to all member radio stations nationally over the same broadcast-quality telephone line, the move allowed ABC to have as many as 4 affiliates in one city – a major competitive advantage and a dramatic turning point in the history of network radio.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Two additional news networks, *ABC Rock* and *ABC Direction*, were added on January 4, 1982, after the network became a satellite-delivered service.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] The network was strict in its insistence that there be no simultaneous broadcast of more than a single network in a market, except during crisis or special event coverage.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] After the sale of most of ABC's radio assets to Citadel Broadcasting in 2007, the ABC Radio Network was operated by the broadcaster as part of the Citadel Media Networks division, and still distributed ABC News content.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Citadel Broadcasting was later acquired by Cumulus Media.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] In July 2014, Cumulus announced that it would end its partnership with ABC News, and begin a new partnership with CNN to syndicate news content via the new Westwood One News network for its stations, beginning on January 1, 2015.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] In turn, ABC announced that it would take the syndication of its radio content in-house under a revived ABC Radio.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Despite many of ABC's former heritage radio properties no longer carrying any ABC programming, ABC affiliated with some other heritage radio stations, including WTOP-FM Washington, WLW Cincinnati, KOA Denver, KOMO Seattle, KTRS St.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Louis, KSL Salt Lake City, and KMBZ Kansas City.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Before being acquired by Westwood One, ABC News Radio programming was available in podcast form on iHeartRadio due to Cumulus radio stations streaming on iHeart.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] When Cumulus started using Westwood One/CNN for their national news, ABC News Radio's digital presence was moved exclusively to Slacker (now LiveOne) until 2020, when it was replaced with news from Associated Press.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] On July 9, 2020, Westwood One made the decision to fold its news network on August 30, and shortly thereafter, Cumulus reaffiliated most of its news/talk stations with ABC with a handful of others affiliating with other networks.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] While those ABC's heritage radio stations used Westwood One News as their national news provider, a few Cumulus stations formerly affiliated with ABC (example KARN-FM Little Rock) carry CBS.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] On May 21, 2026, Audacy, Inc. reaffiliated its heritage CBS News Radio affiliates (including KCBS/San Francisco, KNX Los Angeles, WBBM/Chicago, WCCO/Minneapolis, and WWJ/Detroit among others) with ABC News Radio, ahead of the service's closure the following day.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Of the 6 networks, only Information, Entertainment and ABC FM News remain as separate newscast services today, with their programming delivered via satellite.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] The "Information" network newscasts clear on major-market stations.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] "Entertainment" network news airs mainly on small and medium-market stations.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] ABC FM News newscasts air on a small number of FM music stations.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] These ABC News Radio newscasts originate from the news division's bureaus in New York, Washington and Los Angeles and air exactly at the top of the hour.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] The standard format is the same for all three, with the Entertainment and FM networks having shorter stories and the Information network having slightly longer stories and more global coverage.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Individual soundbites and reporter packages are fed to stations via satellite and an affiliate website.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] In addition to the top-of-the-hour newscasts, ABC News also provides its radio affiliates with headlines, briefs and "status reports" that air every 10 minutes, as well as special reports, special event coverage and long form programming.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] ABC News Radio produced *News and Comment*, a twice-daily long-form program hosted by broadcaster Paul Harvey, who also would read the program's commercial messages in a seamless transition.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] This program originated from Chicago and began its run in 1951.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] On January 1, 1968, *News and Comment* became a part of ABC's "American Entertainment Network", although the program was also heard on stations affiliated with the other ABC Networks, if the "Entertainment" affiliate was not as powerful as another ABC affiliate in a given market.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] A 5-minute long spin-off voiced by Harvey, *The Rest of the Story*, began in May 1976 and was offered to affiliates in the late afternoons, as well as on Saturday mornings.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] After Paul Harvey's death on February 28, 2009, San Francisco-based broadcaster Gil Gross was appointed as the new host of *News and Comment*, while the *Rest of the Story* time slot was held by Doug Limerick.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Shortly after their appointments, however, Mike Huckabee was hired to host his own thrice-daily commentary program, *The Huckabee Report*, offered to stations that had been carrying both programs in the same time slots.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] This program, however, was produced by the former ABC Radio Network, at that point rebranded as Citadel Media, eventually becoming Cumulus Media, and finally Westwood One.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Huckabee took over distribution of the program himself as a digital-only feature in 2015.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] The channel also existed on Sirius Canada until February 2007.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Each morning, the channel featured a six-hour news wheel, produced by ABC News Radio.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] In the afternoon, hourly newscasts preceded some of ABC Radio's top talk show talent, like Sean Hannity, KABC's Larry Elder and WBAP's Mark Davis.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] ABC News And Talk used to host a mid-day talk show exclusively for satellite radio titled *Live from 125*.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] The show's host was rotated on a weekly basis so there were several different program personalities.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] In September 2006, John Batchelor took a leave of absence from the ABC Radio network.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Mark Levin took his place on the ABC News And Talk lineup.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] Levin's show was broadcast on a 2-hour tape-delay basis, which was assumed to be twofold: to protect Elder's spot in the lineup, since Elder had the slot prior to Levin's arrival, and so Levin can continue to grow his terrestrial affiliate base.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] The channel was programmed by ABC Radio until June 12, 2007, when it was turned over to Citadel Broadcasting as part of the divestiture by ABC parent Disney of nearly all of its radio assets.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-radio] The network was shut down September 24, 2007.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] ABC began in 1943 as the NBC Blue Network, a radio network that was spun off from NBC, as ordered by the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) in 1942.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] The reason for the order was to expand competition in radio broadcasting in the United States, specifically news and political broadcasting, and broaden the projected points of view.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Only a few companies, such as NBC and CBS, dominated the radio market.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] NBC conducted the split voluntarily in case its appeal of the ruling was denied, and it was forced to split its two networks into separate companies.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Regular television news broadcasts on ABC began soon after the network signed on its initial owned-and-operated television station (WJZ-TV, now WABC-TV) and production center in New York City in August 1948.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Broadcasts continued as the ABC network expanded nationwide.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Until the early 1970s, ABC News programs and ABC in general consistently ranked third in viewership behind CBS and NBC news programs.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] ABC had fewer affiliate stations and a weaker prime-time programming slate to support the network's news operations compared to the two larger networks, each of which had established their radio news operations during the 1930s.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] By the 1970s, the network had effectively turned around, with its prime-time entertainment programs achieving more substantial ratings and drawing in higher advertising revenue and profits for ABC overall.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] With the appointment of the president of ABC Sports, Roone Arledge as president of ABC News in 1977, ABC invested the resources to make it a significant source of news content.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Arledge, known for experimenting with the broadcast "model", created many of ABC News' most popular and enduring programs, including *20/20*, *World News Tonight*, *This Week*, *Nightline*, and *Primetime Live*.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] In June 1998, ABC News (which owned an 80% stake in the service), Nine Network and ITN sold their respective interests in Worldwide Television News to the Associated Press.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Additionally, ABC News signed a multi-year content deal with AP for its affiliate video service, Associated Press Television News (APTV), while providing material from ABC's news video service, ABC News One, to APTV.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Scandal erupted on October 7, 1985, over a decision by Arledge, president of ABC News and Sports, to kill a 13-minute report about Marilyn Monroe, possibly due to his close ties to Ethel Kennedy.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] *20/20* drew criticism from the program's co-anchors, Hugh Downs and Barbara Walters, and the executive producer, Av Westin.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Arledge said that he had killed the piece because it was "gossip-column stuff" and "does not live up to its billing." Downs, however, took issue with Arledge's judgment.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] "I am upset about the way it was handled," he said in an interview.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] "I honestly believe that this is more carefully documented than anything any network did during Watergate.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] I lament the fact that the decision reflects badly on people I respect and it reflects badly on me and the broadcast." Additionally, Westin said: "I don't anticipate not putting it on the air.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] We are documenting that there was a relationship between Bobby and Marilyn and Jack and Marilyn.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Fred Otash, a detective who said he was the chief wiretapper, is interviewed on camera, and ABC staff members said three other wiretappers corroborated his account.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] In addition, several people not in the book say on camera that Monroe kept diaries with references to meetings with the Kennedy brothers, according to a staff member who has seen the report.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] "It set out to be a piece which would demonstrate that because of alleged relations between Robert Kennedy and John F.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Kennedy and Monroe, the presidency was compromised because organized crime was involved," he said.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] "Based on what has been uncovered so far, there was no evidence." Arledge's decision to kill the broadcast resulted in the subsequent decision of Geraldo Rivera to leave ABC entirely.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Rivera was a *20/20* correspondent but did not work on that story.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] He had been publicly critical of Arledge's decision.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Arledge, a champion and defender of Rivera, said he thought the story needed more work.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] The story probed purported affairs between actress Marilyn Monroe, President John F.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] On August 7, 2014, ABC announced that it would relaunch its radio network division, ABC Radio, on January 1, 2015.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] The change occurred following the announcement that Cumulus would replace its ABC News radio service with Westwood One News (via CNN).
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] On September 20, 2019, ABC Radio was renamed as ABC Audio as the network has evolved to offer a podcast portfolio and other forms of on-demand and linear content.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] In April 2018, it was announced that *FiveThirtyEight* would be transferred to ABC News from ESPN, Inc., majority owned by the Walt Disney Company.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] On September 10, 2018, ABC News launched a second attempt to extend its *Good Morning America* brand into the afternoon with *GMA3: What You Need to Know*.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] In May 2019, *ABC News Live*, a news focused streaming channel, was launched on Roku.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Following a reorganization of ABC's parent company, The Walt Disney Company which created the Walt Disney Direct-to-Consumer and International segment in March 2018, ABC News Digital and Live Streaming, including *ABC News Live* and *FiveThirtyEight*, were transferred to the new segment.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] In an October 2018 Simmons Research survey of 38 news organizations, ABC News was ranked the second most trusted news organization by Americans, behind *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] In December 2024, ABC's owner, the Walt Disney Company, settled a defamation lawsuit brought by Donald Trump against ABC News, by agreeing to donate $15 million to Trump's future presidential library foundation and paying $1 million in Trump's legal fees.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Disney also agreed to ABC and anchor George Stephanopoulos publishing a statement saying they regretted that Stephanopoulos, in an interview, had repeatedly said that Trump had been found liable for raping E.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] In November 2025, President Donald Trump became angry with an ABC News reporter for asking a question about the Jeffrey Epstein case and called for the revocation of the network's broadcasting license.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] The website initially had a dedicated staff of about 30.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] In addition to articles, it featured short video clips and audio from the start, delivered using RealAudio and RealVideo technology.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Some content was also available via America Online.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] In 2011, ABC News and Yahoo News announced a strategic partnership to share ABC's online reporting on Yahoo's website; the deal expanded in 2015 to include the Disney/ABC Television Group.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] In 2018, ABC News, and *Good Morning America* specifically, ended the hosting partnership with Yahoo, instead opting to continue separate web presences.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] The service is under the direction of Justin Dial, Vice President of Streaming Content, Seniboye Tienabeso, Executive Director of ABC News Live, Chandra Zeikel, Executive Producer and Eric Ortega, Executive Producer.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Satellite News Channel was a joint venture between ABC News and Group W that launched on June 21, 1982, as a satellite-delivered cable television network.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] SNC used footage from ABC News and seven Washington, D.C.–based crews and stories from other overseas networks to provide a rotating newscast every 20 minutes.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] However, this channel had difficulty getting clearance from cable systems, so ABC News and Group W decided to sell it to its competitor, CNN (a subsidiary of Time Warner's Turner Broadcasting System).
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] CNN ceased Satellite News Channel's operations on October 27, 1983.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] SNC was either replaced by CNN or CNN2 on most cable systems.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] ABC News Now was a 24-hour cable news network that launched on July 26, 2004, as a digital subchannel by ABC News, being the company's second attempt in the 24-hour cable news world after Satellite News Channel.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] It was offered via digital television, broadband and streaming video at ABCNews.com and on mobile phones.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] It delivered breaking news, headline news each half hour, and a wide range of entertainment and lifestyle programming.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] The channel was available in the United States and Europe.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Its Talk Back feature allowed viewers to voice their input by submitting videos and personal thoughts on controversial issues and current topics.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] It was shut down as a digital subchannel after its experimental phase ended with the Presidential inauguration in 2005.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] ABC News Now was replaced on cable providers with Fusion on October 28, 2013.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Fusion was a digital cable and satellite network owned and operated by Fusion Media Group, LLC, which was a joint venture between ABC News and Univision Communications.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] ABC and Univision formally announced their launch on May 2, 2012.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Launched on October 28, 2013, Fusion features a mix of traditional news and investigative programs along with satirical content aimed at English-speaking Hispanic and Latino American adults between the ages of 18 and 34.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] The network replaced ABC News Now, a mainly streaming service of ABC News content.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] In December 2015, it was reported that Disney was in talks to sell its stake in Fusion to Univision.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] The split was complete on April 21, 2016; Univision alone would continue to operate Fusion until December 31, 2021, when it shut down the network.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] In March 2024, Donald Trump filed a defamation lawsuit against ABC News and George Stephanopoulos for defamation, alleging that Stephanopoulos's statements during an interview of Trump on *This Week* were "false, intentional, malicious and designed to cause harm".
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Jean Carroll had sued Trump for rape and sexual assault; the jury in the case, *Carroll II*, had found him liable for sexual assault and awarded Carroll $5 million in damages.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] In July, ABC News moved to dismiss the case, citing Judge Kaplan's comments that Carroll's rape accusation was "substantially true"; the motion was rejected by the presiding judge.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] In December, after Trump had won the 2024 presidential election, ABC News settled the defamation lawsuit a day after a judge ruled that both Trump and Stephanopoulos were required to sit for depositions in the case.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Legal experts said that the settlement, which occurred prior to motions for summary judgments, was agreed to earlier than is typical in the pre-trial procedures of defamation cases.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] They said that it may have been linked to Trump's status as a president-elect or was negotiated to avoid turning over potentially damaging information in the discovery process.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] The *New York Times* reported that according to company insiders Disney leadership was concerned that a Trump-friendly jury in Florida might potentially award Trump a sum exceeding the settlement, to be followed by a risky appeals process.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] The terms of the settlement required ABC News to pay $15 million to Trump's presidential library and $1 million to cover Trump's legal fees, as well as issue a public apology expressing regret for Stephanopoulos's inaccurate claims against Trump.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] Coincidentally, that country's public broadcasting, the Australian Broadcasting Corporation, operates its unrelated news division that is also named ABC News.
[src:chicago-tribune/abc-news-united-states] ABC News maintains a content-sharing agreement with the Nine Network, which also broadcasts *GMA* domestically in the early morning before its own breakfast program.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] Critics of the group, including the Southern Poverty Law Center and the Center for American Progress, describe it as a hate group.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] It has been called the U.S.'s largest anti-Muslim organization.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] Since 2017, the group has organized rallies in support of Donald Trump.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] The group's founder and central figure is the Lebanese-American conservative activist Brigitte Gabriel, a Maronite Catholic.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] Guy Rodgers, a Republican consultant who was National Field Director for the Christian Coalition of America in the 1990s, is executive director.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] The group was established in 2007, and grew out of the American Congress for Truth, which Gabriel established in 2002 to promote her beliefs, books, and public appearance.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] The American Congress for Truth was later renamed Act! for America Education and "continues to operate as a separate non-profit tax-exempt organization".
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] Political scientist Nadia Marzouki identified ACT for America as part of an "echo chamber of Islamophobic misinformation".
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] The group has been described as anti-Muslim by the Florida Center for Investigative Reporting, *Buzzfeed News* and the Independent, and a hate group by the Center for American Progress and the Southern Poverty Law Center.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] The Anti-Defamation League states that the "ACT stokes irrational fear of Muslims" through spreading misinformation and that it "propagates the hateful conspiracy theory" that there is a Muslim plot to impose Islamic law in the U.S.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] The organization has been considered a part of the counter-jihad movement.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] According to *The New York Times*, the conspiracy theorist Frank Gaffney, "a hawkish policy analyst and commentator, who has been known to take polarizing positions", described the group as a "force multiplier" in promoting laws proposed by David Yerushalmi.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] ACT members have introduced Yerushalmi's anti-foreign law bill (also known as anti-Sharia bill) in several state legislatures, accompanying it with "a public outreach blitz about the 'threat' of Sharia to America".
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] ACT has lobbied state and federal officials, seeking "to impact national security policy".
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] King, Republican of New York, who appeared on ACT's "internet television show before hosting a series of hearings on radicalization that singled out Muslims in 2011".
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] Flynn as a member of its board; Flynn has criticized Islam in ways similar to ACT, such as that the Muslim faith itself is one of the root causes of Islamist terrorism; that Islam as a political ideology rather than a religion; that it is a malignant cancer; and that "fear of Muslims is rational".
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] The group has published voter guides and congressional scorecards, and as of 2014 employed a full-time congressional lobbyist, Lisa Piraneo, who is the group's director of government relations.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] In an e-mail distributed in July 2011, the group stated: "ACT! for America does not believe, nor advocate, that all Muslims are engaged in stealth jihad.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] The Anti-Defamation League writes that while ACT's leadership denies holding bigoted views, "the group often argues against the distinction between radical and mainstream Islam".
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] According to the ADL, ACT had posted an article on its website titled "Stop Muslim immigration to the United States" and has promoted a petition demanding that the U.S.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] "stop all immigration into free countries by Muslims while we can" because "WE HAVE NO way of determining which Muslims subscribe to pure Islam.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] The reason this matters is that pure Islam is seditious".
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] A spokesman for the group at a 2016 town meeting near Missoula, Montana promoted conspiracy theories that Muslim immigrants were importing Islamic law into the U.S.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] ACT for America subsequently cancelled its planned June 10 anti-Muslim March Against Sharia in Portland, moving it to Seattle.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] The *Seattle Times* described the rally's stated goal as "purportedly to raise awareness of the practices of genital mutilation and cutting of young girls and women, which the organization attributes to the practice of Sharia law by faithful Muslims".
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] Despite the group's claim that female genital mutilation (FGM) is a solely religious practice, the Anti-Defamation League noted that FGM is not sanctioned or even mentioned in the Quran or Sharia law.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] ACT for America demonstrators in New York City, Chicago, Santa Clara, Seattle, and other cities were outnumbered by counter-protesters.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] The marches were also attended by right-wing extremist groups such as militia members and white supremacists.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] Demonstrators in front of Trump Tower Chicago also expressed support for President Donald Trump.
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] The group describes itself as a nonpartisan and nonreligious national security group and its base of support comes from "evangelical Christian conservatives, hard-line defenders of Israel (both Jews and Christians) and Tea Party Republicans".
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] In 2011, the group said it had "500 chapters and 155,000 members nationwide".
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] In 2015, Jordan Denari and Nathan Lean of Georgetown University's Bridge Initiative research project wrote that ACT for America "boasts nearly 300,000 members and 890 chapters across the country".
[src:chicago-tribune/act-for-america] Reporting by *The Independent* and *The Guardian* has referred to the group as the largest anti-Muslim group in the U.S.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL was at one point the most recognized brand on the Web in the United States.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL once provided a dial-up Internet service to millions of Americans and pioneered instant messaging and chat rooms with AOL Instant Messenger (AIM).
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In 1998, AOL purchased Netscape for US$4.2 billion.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] By 2000, AOL was providing internet service to over 20 million consumers, dominating the market of internet service providers (ISPs).
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In 2001, at the height of its popularity, it purchased the media conglomerate Time Warner in the largest merger in US history.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL shrank rapidly thereafter, partly due to the decline of dial-up and rise of broadband.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL was spun off from Time Warner in 2009, with Tim Armstrong appointed the new CEO.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Under his leadership, the company invested in media brands and advertising technologies.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In 2015, AOL was acquired by Verizon Communications for $4.4 billion, and was merged with Yahoo! the following year after the latter was also acquired by Verizon.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In May 2021, Verizon announced it would sell Verizon Media (and thus AOL) to private equity firm Apollo Global Management for $5 billion, and the sale was completed at the end of August.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In October 2025, Apollo reached a $1.5 billion deal to sell AOL to the Italian conglomerate Bending Spoons.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL began in 1983, as a short-lived venture called **Control Video Corporation** (**CVC**), founded by William von Meister.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Its sole product was an online service called GameLine for the Atari 2600 video game console, after von Meister's idea of buying music on demand was rejected by Warner Communications.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Subscribers bought a modem from the company for $49.95 and paid a one-time $15 setup fee.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] GameLine permitted subscribers to temporarily download games and keep track of high scores, at a cost of $1 per game.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The telephone disconnected and the downloaded game would remain in GameLine's Master Module, playable until the user turned off the console or downloaded another game.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In January 1983, Steve Case was hired as a marketing consultant for Control Video on the recommendation of his brother, investment banker Dan Case.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In May 1983, Jim Kimsey became a manufacturing consultant for Control Video, which was near bankruptcy.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Kimsey was brought in by his West Point friend Frank Caufield, an investor in the company.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In early 1985, von Meister left the company.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On May 24, 1985, **Quantum Computer Services**, an online services company, was founded by Kimsey from the remnants of Control Video, with Kimsey as chief executive officer and Marc Seriff as chief technology officer.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The technical team consisted of Seriff, Tom Ralston, Ray Heinrich, Steve Trus, Ken Huntsman, Janet Hunter, Dave Brown, Craig Dykstra, Doug Coward, and Mike Ficco.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In 1987, Case was promoted again to executive vice-president.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Kimsey soon began to groom Case to take over the role of CEO, which he did when Kimsey retired in 1991.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Kimsey changed the company's strategy, and in 1985, launched a dedicated online service for Commodore 64 and 128 computers, originally called Quantum Link ("Q-Link" for short).
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The Quantum Link software was based on software licensed from PlayNet, Inc., which was founded in 1983 by Howard Goldberg and Dave Panzl.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The service was different from other online services as it used the computing power of the Commodore 64 and the Apple II rather than just a "dumb" terminal.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] It passed tokens back and forth and provided a fixed-price service tailored for home users.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In May 1988, Quantum and Apple launched AppleLink Personal Edition for Apple II and Macintosh computers.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In August 1988, Quantum launched PC Link, a service for IBM-compatible PCs developed in a joint venture with the Tandy Corporation.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] After the company parted ways with Apple in October 1989, Quantum changed the service's name to America Online.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Case promoted and sold AOL as the online service for people unfamiliar with computers, in contrast to CompuServe, which was well established in the technical community.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] From the beginning, AOL included online games in its mix of products; many classic and casual games were included in the original PlayNet software system.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In February 1991, AOL for IBM PC compatibles running MS-DOS was launched using a GeoWorks interface; it was followed a year later by AOL for Windows 3.0.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] This coincided with growth in pay-based online services, like Prodigy, CompuServe, and GEnie.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] During the early 1990s, the average subscription lasted for about 25 months and accounted for $350 in total revenue.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Advertisements invited modem owners to "Try America Online FREE", promising free software and trial membership.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL discontinued Q-Link and PC Link in late 1994.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In September 1993, AOL added Usenet access to its features.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] This is commonly referred to as the "Eternal September", as Usenet's cycle of new users was previously dominated by smaller numbers of college and university freshmen gaining access in September and taking a few weeks to acclimate.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] This also coincided with a new "carpet bombing" marketing campaign by CMO Jan Brandt to distribute as many free trial AOL trial disks as possible through nonconventional distribution partners.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] At one point, 50% of the CDs produced worldwide had an AOL logo.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL quickly surpassed GEnie, and by the mid-1990s, it passed Prodigy (which for several years allowed AOL advertising) and CompuServe.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In November 1994, AOL purchased Booklink for its web browser, to give its users web access.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In 1996, AOL replaced Booklink with a browser based on Internet Explorer, reportedly in exchange for inclusion of AOL in Windows.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL purchased search engine WebCrawler in 1995, but sold it to Excite the following year; the deal made Excite the sole search and directory service on AOL.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] After the deal closed in March 1997, AOL launched its own branded search engine, based on Excite, called NetFind.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL charged its users an hourly fee until December 1996, when the company changed to a flat monthly rate of $19.95.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] During this time, AOL connections were flooded with users trying to connect, and many canceled their accounts due to constant busy signals.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] A commercial was made featuring Steve Case telling people AOL was working day and night to fix the problem.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Within three years, AOL's user base grew to 10 million people.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In 1995, AOL was headquartered at 8619 Westwood Center Drive in the Tysons Corner CDP in unincorporated Fairfax County, Virginia in the Washington, D.C. metropolitan area. near the Town of Vienna.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL was quickly running out of room in October 1996 for its network at the Fairfax County campus.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In mid-1996, AOL moved to 22000 AOL Way in Dulles, unincorporated Loudoun County, Virginia to provide room for future growth.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In a five-year landmark agreement with the most popular operating system, AOL was bundled with Windows software.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On March 31, 1996, the short-lived eWorld was purchased by AOL.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In 1997, about half of all US homes with Internet access had it through AOL.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] During this time, AOL's content channels, under Jason Seiken, including News, Sports, and Entertainment, experienced their greatest growth as AOL become the dominant online service internationally with more than 34 million subscribers.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On August 7, 1996, AOL experienced a total outage starting at 1:00 AM PST that would last nineteen hours and took over six million people offline.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In February 1998, AOL acquired CompuServe Interactive Services (CIS) via WorldCom (later Verizon), which kept Compuware's networking business.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In November 1998, AOL announced it would acquire Netscape, best known for their web browser, in a major $4.2 billion deal.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Another large acquisition in December 1999 was that of MapQuest, for $1.1 billion.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In January 2000, as new broadband technologies were being rolled out around the New York City metropolitan area and elsewhere across the United States, AOL and Time Warner announced plans to merge, forming AOL Time Warner, Inc.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The terms of the deal called for AOL shareholders to own 55% of the new, combined company.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The new company was led by executives from AOL, SBI, and Time Warner.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Gerald Levin, who had served as CEO of Time Warner, was CEO of the new company.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Michael Kelly (from AOL) was the chief financial officer, Robert W.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Pittman (from AOL) and Dick Parsons (from Time Warner) served as co-chief operating officers.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In 2002, Jonathan Miller became CEO of AOL.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The following year, AOL Time Warner dropped the "AOL" from its name.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] It was the largest merger in history when completed with the combined value of the companies at $360 billion.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] This value fell sharply, to as low as $120 billion, as markets repriced AOL's valuation as a pure internet firm more modestly when combined with the traditional media and cable business.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] This status did not last long, and the company's value rose again within three months.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] By the end of that year, the tide had turned against "pure" internet companies, with many collapsing under falling stock prices, and even the strongest companies in the field losing up to 75% of their market value.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The decline continued through 2001, but even with the losses, AOL was among the internet giants that continued to outperform brick and mortar companies.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In 2004, along with the launch of AOL 9.0 Optimized, AOL also made available the option of personalized greetings which would enable the user to hear his or her name while accessing basic functions and mail alerts, or while logging in or out.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In 2005, AOL broadcast the Live 8 concert live over the Internet, and thousands of users downloaded clips of the concert over the following months.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In late 2005, AOL released AOL Safety & Security Center, a bundle of McAfee Antivirus, CA anti-spyware, and proprietary firewall and phishing protection software.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] News reports in late 2005 identified companies such as Yahoo!, Microsoft, and Google as candidates for turning AOL into a joint venture.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Those plans were abandoned when it was revealed on December 20, 2005, that Google would purchase a 5% share of AOL for $1 billion.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On April 3, 2006, AOL announced that it would retire the full name America Online.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The official name of the service became AOL, and the full name of the Time Warner subdivision became AOL LLC.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On June 8, 2006, AOL offered a new program called AOL Active Security Monitor, a diagnostic tool to monitor and rate PC security status, and recommended additional security software from AOL or Download.com.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Two months later, AOL released AOL Active Virus Shield, a free product developed by Kaspersky Lab, that did not require an AOL account, only an internet email address.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The ISP side of AOL UK was bought by Carphone Warehouse in October 2006 to take advantage of its 100,000 LLU customers, making Carphone Warehouse the largest LLU provider in the UK.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In August 2006, AOL announced that it would offer email accounts and software previously available only to its paying customers, provided that users accessed AOL or AOL.com through an access method not owned by AOL (otherwise known as "third party transit", "bring your own access" or "BYOA").
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The move was designed to reduce costs associated with the "walled garden" business model by reducing usage of AOL-owned access points and shifting members with high-speed internet access from client-based usage to the more lucrative advertising provider AOL.com.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The change from paid to free access was also designed to slow the rate at which members canceled their accounts and defected to Microsoft Hotmail, Yahoo! or other free email providers.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Also in August, AOL informed its US customers of an increase in the price of its dial-up access to $25.90.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The increase was part of an effort to migrate the service's remaining dial-up users to broadband, as the increased price was the same as that of its monthly DSL access.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] However, AOL subsequently began offering unlimited dial-up access for $9.95 a month.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On November 16, 2006, Randy Falco succeeded Jonathan Miller as CEO.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In December 2006, AOL closed its last remaining call center in the United States, "taking the America out of America Online," according to industry pundits.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Service centers based in India and the Philippines continue to provide customer support and technical assistance to subscribers.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On September 17, 2007, AOL announced the relocation of one of its corporate headquarters from Dulles, Virginia to New York City and the combination of its advertising units into a new subsidiary called Platform A.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] This action followed several advertising acquisitions, most notably Advertising.com, and highlighted the company's new focus on advertising-driven business models.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL management stressed that "significant operations" would remain in Dulles, which included the company's access services and modem banks.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In October 2007, AOL announced the relocation of its other headquarters from Loudoun County, Virginia to New York City, while continuing to operate its Virginia offices.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] As part of the move to New York and the restructuring of responsibilities at the Dulles headquarters complex after the Reston move, Falco announced on October 15, 2007, plans to lay off 2,000 employees worldwide by the end of 2007, beginning "immediately".
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The result was a layoff of approximately 40% of AOL's employees.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Most compensation packages associated with the October 2007 layoffs included a minimum of 120 days of severance pay, 60 of which were offered in lieu of the 60-day advance notice requirement by provisions of the 1988 federal WARN Act.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] By November 2007, AOL's customer base had been reduced to 10.1 million subscribers, slightly more than the number of subscribers of Comcast and AT&T Yahoo!.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] According to Falco, as of December 2007, the conversion rate of accounts from paid access to free access was more than 80%.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On January 3, 2008, AOL announced the closing of its Reston, Virginia, data center, which was sold to CRG West.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On February 6, Time Warner CEO Jeff Bewkes announced that Time Warner would divide AOL's internet-access and advertising businesses, with the possibility of later selling the internet-access division.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On March 13, 2008, AOL purchased the social networking site Bebo for $850 million (£417 million).
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On July 25, AOL announced that it was shuttering Xdrive, AOL Pictures and BlueString to save on costs and focus on its core advertising business.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On October 31, AOL Hometown (a web-hosting service for the websites of AOL customers) and the AOL Journal blog hosting service were eliminated.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On March 12, 2009, Tim Armstrong, formerly with Google, was named chairman and CEO of AOL.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On May 28, Time Warner announced that it would position AOL as an independent company after Google's shares ceased at the end of the fiscal year.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On November 23, AOL unveiled a new brand identity with the wordmark "Aol." superimposed onto canvases created by commissioned artists.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The new identity, designed by Wolff Olins, was integrated with all of AOL's services on December 10, the date upon which AOL traded independently for the first time since the Time Warner merger on the New York Stock Exchange under the symbol AOL.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On April 6, 2010, AOL announced plans to shutter or sell Bebo.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On June 16, the property was sold to Criterion Capital Partners for an undisclosed amount, believed to be approximately $10 million.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In December, AIM eliminated access to AOL chat rooms, noting a marked decline in usage in recent months.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Under Armstrong's leadership, AOL followed a new business direction marked by a series of acquisitions.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] It announced the acquisition of Patch Media, a network of community-specific news and information sites focused on towns and communities.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On September 28, 2010, at the San Francisco TechCrunch Disrupt Conference, AOL signed an agreement to acquire TechCrunch.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On December 12, 2010, AOL acquired about.me, a personal profile and identity platform, four days after the platform's public launch.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On January 31, 2011, AOL announced the acquisition of European video distribution network goviral.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In March 2011, AOL acquired *HuffPost* for $315 million.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Shortly after the acquisition was announced, *Huffington Post* co-founder Arianna Huffington replaced AOL content chief David Eun, assuming the role of president and editor-in-chief of the AOL Huffington Post Media Group.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On March 10, AOL announced that it would cut approximately 900 workers following the *HuffPost* acquisition.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On September 14, 2011, AOL formed a strategic ad-selling partnership with two of its largest competitors, Yahoo and Microsoft.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The three companies would begin selling inventory on each other's sites.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The strategy was designed to help the companies compete with Google and advertising networks.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On February 28, 2012, AOL partnered with PBS to launch MAKERS, a digital documentary series focusing on high-achieving women in industries perceived as male-dominated such as war, comedy, space, business, Hollywood and politics.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Subjects for MAKERS episodes have included Oprah Winfrey, Hillary Clinton, Sheryl Sandberg, Martha Stewart, Indra Nooyi, Lena Dunham and Ellen DeGeneres.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On March 15, 2012, AOL announced the acquisition of Hipster, a mobile photo-sharing app, for an undisclosed amount.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On April 9, 2012, AOL announced a deal to sell 800 patents to Microsoft for $1.056 billion.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The deal included a perpetual license for AOL to use the patents.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In April, AOL took several steps to expand its ability to generate revenue through online video advertising.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The company announced that it would offer gross rating point (GRP) guarantee for online video, mirroring the television-ratings system and guaranteeing audience delivery for online-video advertising campaigns bought across its properties.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] This announcement came just days before the Digital Content NewFront (DCNF) a two-week event held by AOL, Google, Hulu, Microsoft, Vevo and Yahoo to showcase the participating sites' digital video offerings.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The DCNF was conducted in advance of the traditional television upfronts in the hope of diverting more advertising money into the digital space.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On April 24, the company launched the AOL On network, a single website for its video output.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In February 2013, AOL reported its fourth quarter revenue of $599.5 million, its first growth in quarterly revenue in eight years.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In August 2013, Armstrong announced that Patch Media would scale back or sell hundreds of its local news sites.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Not long afterward, layoffs began, with up to 500 out of 1,100 positions initially impacted.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On January 15, 2014, Patch Media was spun off, and majority ownership was held by Hale Global.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] By the end of 2014, AOL controlled 0.74% of the global advertising market, well behind industry leader Google's 31.4%.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On January 23, 2014, AOL acquired Gravity, a software startup that tracked users' online behavior and tailored ads and content based on their interests, for $83 million.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The deal, which included approximately 40 Gravity employees and the company's personalization technology, was Armstrong's fourth-largest deal since taking command in 2009.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Later that year, AOL acquired Vidible, a company that developed technology to help websites run video content from other publishers, and help video publishers sell their content to these websites.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The deal, which was announced December 1, 2014, was reportedly worth roughly $50 million.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On July 16, 2014, AOL earned an Emmy nomination for the AOL original series *The Future Starts Here* in the News and Documentary category.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] This came days after AOL earned its first Primetime Emmy Award nomination and win for *Park Bench with Steve Buscemi* in the Outstanding Short Form Variety Series.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Created and hosted by Tiffany Shlain, the series focused on humans' relationship with technology and featured episodes such as "The Future of Our Species", "Why We Love Robots" and "A Case for Optimism".
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On May 12, 2015, Verizon announced plans to buy AOL for $50 per share in a deal valued at $4.4 billion.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The transaction was completed on June 23.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Armstrong, who continued to lead the firm following regulatory approval, called the deal the logical next step for AOL.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] "If you look forward five years, you're going to be in a space where there are going to be massive, global-scale networks, and there's no better partner for us to go forward with than Verizon." he said.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] "It's really not about selling the company today.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Analyst David Bank said he thought the deal made sense for Verizon.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The deal will broaden Verizon's advertising sales platforms and increase its video production ability through websites such as *HuffPost*, TechCrunch, and Engadget.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] However, Craig Moffett said it was unlikely the deal would make a big difference to Verizon's bottom line.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL had about two million dial-up subscribers at the time of the buyout.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The announcement caused AOL's stock price to rise 17%, while Verizon's stock price dropped slightly.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Shortly before the Verizon purchase, on April 14, 2015, AOL launched ONE by AOL, a digital marketing programmatic platform that unifies buying channels and audience management platforms to track and optimize campaigns over multiple screens.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Later that year, on September 15, AOL expanded the product with ONE by AOL: Creative, which is geared towards creative and media agencies to similarly connect marketing and ad distribution efforts.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On May 8, 2015, AOL reported its first-quarter revenue of $625.1 million, $483.5 million of which came from advertising and related operations, marking a 7% increase from Q1 2014.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Over that year, the AOL Platforms division saw a 21% increase in revenue, but a drop in adjusted OIBDA due to increased investments in the company's video and programmatic platforms.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On June 29, 2015, AOL announced a deal with Microsoft to take over the majority of its digital advertising business.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Under the pact, as many as 1,200 Microsoft employees involved with the business will be transferred to AOL, and the company will take over the sale of display, video, and mobile ads on various Microsoft platforms in nine countries, including Brazil, Canada, the United States, and the United Kingdom.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Additionally, Google Search will be replaced on AOL properties with Bing—which will display advertising sold by Microsoft.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Both advertising deals are subject to affiliate marketing revenue sharing.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On September 3, 2015, AOL agreed to buy Millennial Media for $238 million.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On October 23, 2015, AOL completed the acquisition.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On October 1, 2015, Go90, a free ad-supported mobile video service aimed at young adult and teen viewers that Verizon owns and AOL oversees and operates, launched its content publicly after months of beta testing.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The initial launch line-up included content from Comedy Central, HuffPost, Nerdist News, Univision News, Vice, ESPN and MTV.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On April 20, 2016, AOL acquired virtual reality studio RYOT to bring immersive 360 degree video and VR content to HuffPost's global audience across desktop, mobile, and apps.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In July 2016, Verizon Communications announced its intent to purchase the core internet business of Yahoo!.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Verizon merged AOL with Yahoo into a new company called "Oath Inc.", which in January 2019 rebranded itself as Verizon Media.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In April 2018, Oath Inc. sold Moviefone to MoviePass Parent Helios and Matheson Analytics.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In November 2020 the *Huffington Post* was sold to BuzzFeed in a stock deal.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On May 3, 2021, Verizon announced it would sell 90 percent of its Verizon Media division to Apollo Global Management for $5 billion, becoming the second independent incarnation of Yahoo Inc.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In 2025, AOL ended its dial-up internet service.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In October 2025, Bending Spoons acquired AOL in a deal valued at roughly $1.5 billion.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In a statement, Bending Spoons CEO Luca Ferrari cited AOL's 30 million active users as part of what made the property attractive.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The purchase was quietly completed in January 2026, Bending Spoons then laid off more than 100 AOL employees in February 2026.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL's web ecosystem operates primarily as a content aggregator and digital service portal.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The AOL homepage aggregates news, lifestyle, and entertainment content from major syndicated third-party media wires and partner networks.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In addition to mobile-optimized web experiences, AOL produces mobile applications for its remaining properties and standalone software utilities.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL Mail is AOL's proprietary email client.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] It provides fully integrated webmail services and direct links to news headlines on AOL content sites.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL Plans offers multiple online safety and assistance subscription bundles: identity theft protection, data security tools, and a general online technical assistance service.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] In 2017, a paid internet suite version called AOL Desktop Gold was released, available for $4.99 per month after a trial period.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] It replaced the previous free software tier.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On January 10, 2018, all versions of the original AOL Desktop were shut down so AOL could focus towards AOL Desktop Gold and AOL Shield.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Following the shutdown of AIM, AOL's original legacy chat rooms continued to be accessible through AOL Desktop Gold until the chat system was permanently shut down on December 15, 2020.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] When it owned the Huffington Post, AOL's content ecosystem featured contributors consisting of over 20,000 bloggers, including politicians, celebrities, academics, and policy experts, who contributed on a wide range of topics.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Several major media brands formerly owned by AOL—including Engadget, Autoblog, TechCrunch, and Built by Girls—became part of Verizon Media (now Yahoo) following Verizon's acquisition of AOL in 2015.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Mobile applications and experimental products associated with these eras, such as Alto, Pip, and Vivv, have also been retired.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL previously operated a global portfolio of advertising technologies and services.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] This included data and programmatic solutions handled through its proprietary ad technology stack, ONE by AOL, which was built on acquisitions such as AdapTV (2013), Convertro (2014), Precision Demand (2014), and Vidible (2014).
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] ONE by AOL operated under two separate banners: ONE by AOL for Publishers and ONE by AOL for Advertisers.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] On September 10, 2018, parent company Oath consolidated BrightRoll, One by AOL, and Yahoo Gemini into a unified ad-tech platform named Oath Ad Platforms, which was later rebranded as Yahoo!
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL originally built its user base on Dial-up Internet access.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] While the service retained 2.1 million subscribers in 2015, membership plummeted to a few thousand by 2021 as remaining premium users transitioned to software support packages.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL officially discontinued its legacy dial-up service on September 30, 2025.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL Instant Messenger (AIM) was AOL's flagship proprietary instant-messaging tool launched in 1997.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] At its peak, billions of messages were sent daily across AIM and associated AOL chat properties.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Over time, it lost significant market share to competitors like Google Chat, Facebook Messenger, and text messaging.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] It also included a integrated video-chat tool, AV by AIM.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] AOL discontinued the AIM service on December 15, 2017.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Subsequent iterations shifted back to supporting the 9.X version lines.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Version 9.8 replaced existing Internet Explorer engine dependencies with the CEF engine to mimic modern web-browsing frameworks like Google Chrome.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Version 11 introduced a complete software architecture rewrite while preserving the 9.8 legacy layout.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The freeware software stack was fully deprecated in 2017 in favor of the paid subscription iteration, AOL Desktop Gold.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] Separately, the company maintained the **AOL Toolbar**, a web browser toolbar distributed as a Mozilla plug-in offering immediate web hooks into fundamental AOL platforms.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p01] The toolbar utility was maintained from 2007 until its retirement in 2018.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] In its earlier incarnation as a "walled garden" community and service provider, AOL received criticism for its community policies, terms of service, and customer service.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Prior to 2006, AOL was known for its direct mailing of CD-ROMs and 3.5-inch floppy disks containing its software.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] The disks were distributed in large numbers; at one point, half of the CDs manufactured worldwide had AOL logos on them.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] The marketing tactic was criticized for its environmental cost, and AOL CDs were recognized as *PC World*'s most annoying tech product.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL used a system of volunteers to moderate its chat rooms, forums and user communities.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] The program dated back to AOL's early days, when it charged by the hour for access and one of its highest billing services was chat.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL provided free access to community leaders in exchange for moderating the chat rooms, and this effectively made chat very cheap to operate, and more lucrative than AOL's other services of the era.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] There were 33,000 community leaders in 1996.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] All community leaders received hours of training and underwent a probationary period.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] While most community leaders moderated chat rooms, some ran AOL communities and controlled their layout and design, with as much as 90% of AOL's content being created or overseen by community managers until 1996.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] By 1996, ISPs were beginning to charge flat rates for unlimited access, which they could do at a profit because they only provided internet access.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Even though AOL would lose money with such a pricing scheme, it was forced by market conditions to offer unlimited access in October 1996.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] In order to return to profitability, AOL rapidly shifted its focus from content creation to advertising, resulting in less of a need to carefully moderate every forum and chat room to keep users willing to pay by the minute to remain connected.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] After unlimited access, AOL considered scrapping the program entirely, but continued it with a reduced number of community leaders, with scaled-back roles in creating content.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Although community leaders continued to receive free access, after 1996 they were motivated more by the prestige of the position and the access to moderator tools and restricted areas within AOL.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] By 1999, there were over 15,000 volunteers in the program.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] In May 1999, two former volunteers filed a class-action lawsuit alleging AOL violated the Fair Labor Standards Act by treating volunteers like employees.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Volunteers had to apply for the position, commit to working for at least three to four hours a week, fill out timecards and sign a non-disclosure agreement.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] On July 22, AOL ended its youth corps, which consisted of 350 underage community leaders.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] At this time, the United States Department of Labor began an investigation into the program, but it came to no conclusions about AOL's practices.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL ended its community leader program on June 8, 2005.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] The class action lawsuit dragged on for years, even after AOL ended the program and AOL declined as a major internet company.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] In 2010, AOL finally agreed to settle the lawsuit for $15 million.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] The community leader program was described as an example of co-production in a 2009 article in *International Journal of Cultural Studies*.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL has faced a number of lawsuits over claims that it has been slow to stop billing customers after their accounts have been canceled, either by the company or the user.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] In addition, AOL changed its method of calculating used minutes in response to a class action lawsuit.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Previously, AOL would add 15 seconds to the time a user was connected to the service and round up to the next whole minute (thus, a person who used the service for 12 minutes and 46 seconds would be charged for 14 minutes).
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL claimed this was to account for sign on/sign off time, but because this practice was not made known to its customers, the plaintiffs won (some also pointed out that signing on and off did not always take 15 seconds, especially when connecting via another ISP).
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL disclosed its connection-time calculation methods to all of its customers and credited them with extra free hours.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] In addition, the AOL software would notify the user of exactly how long they were connected and how many minutes they were being charged.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL was sued by the Ohio Attorney General in October 2003 for improper billing practices.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL agreed to resolve any consumer complaints filed with the Ohio AG's office.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] In December 2006, AOL agreed to provide restitution to Florida consumers to settle the case filed against them by the Florida Attorney General.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Many customers complained that AOL personnel ignored their demands to cancel service and stop billing.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] In response to approximately 300 consumer complaints, the New York Attorney General's office began an inquiry of AOL's customer service policies.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] The investigation revealed that the company had an elaborate scheme for rewarding employees who purported to retain or "save" subscribers who had called to cancel their Internet service.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] In many instances, such retention was done against subscribers' wishes, or without their consent.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Under the scheme, customer service personnel received bonuses worth tens of thousands of dollars if they could successfully dissuade or "save" half of the people who called to cancel service.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] For several years, AOL had instituted minimum retention or "save" percentages, which consumer representatives were expected to meet.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] These bonuses, and the minimum "save" rates accompanying them, had the effect of employees not honoring cancellations, or otherwise making cancellation unduly difficult for consumers.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] On August 24, 2005, America Online agreed to pay $1.25 million to the state of New York and reformed its customer service procedures.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Under the agreement, AOL would no longer require its customer service representatives to meet a minimum quota for customer retention in order to receive a bonus.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] However the agreement only covered people in the state of New York.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] On June 13, 2006, Vincent Ferrari documented his account cancellation phone call in a blog post, stating he had switched to broadband years earlier.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] In the recorded phone call, the AOL representative refused to cancel the account unless the 30-year-old Ferrari explained why AOL hours were still being recorded on it.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Ferrari insisted that AOL software was not even installed on the computer.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] When Ferrari demanded that the account be canceled regardless, the AOL representative asked to speak with Ferrari's father, for whom the account had been set up.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] When CNBC reporters tried to have an account on AOL cancelled, they were hung up on immediately and it ultimately took more than 45 minutes to cancel the account.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] On July 19, 2006, AOL's entire retention manual was released on the Internet.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] On August 3, 2006, Time Warner announced that the company would be dissolving AOL's retention centers due to its profits hinging on $1 billion in cost cuts.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] The company estimated that it would lose more than six million subscribers over the following year.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Prior to 2006, AOL often sent unsolicited mass direct mail of 31⁄2" floppy disks and CD-ROMs containing their software.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] They were the most frequent user of this marketing tactic, and received criticism for the environmental cost of the campaign.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] According to *PC World*, in the 1990s "you couldn't open a magazine (*PC World* included) or your mailbox without an AOL disk falling out of it".
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] The mass distribution of these disks was seen as wasteful by the public and led to protest groups.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] One such was No More AOL CDs, a web-based effort by two IT workers to collect one million disks with the intent to return the disks to AOL.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] The website was started in August 2001, and an estimated 410,176 CDs were collected by August 2007 when the project was shut down.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] In 2000, AOL was served with an $8 billion lawsuit alleging that its AOL 5.0 software caused significant difficulties for users attempting to use third-party Internet service providers.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] The lawsuit sought damages of up to $1000 for each user that had downloaded the software cited at the time of the lawsuit.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL later agreed to a settlement of $15 million, without admission of wrongdoing.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] The AOL software then was given a feature called AOL Dialer, or AOL Connect on Mac OS X.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] This feature allowed users to connect to the ISP without running the full interface.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] This allowed users to use only the applications they wish to use, especially if they do not favor the AOL Browser.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL 9.0 was once identified by Stopbadware as being *under investigation* for installing additional software without disclosure, and modifying browser preferences, toolbars, and icons.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] However, as of the release of AOL 9.0 VR (Vista Ready) on January 26, 2007, it was no longer considered badware due to changes AOL made in the software.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] When AOL gave clients access to Usenet in 1993, they hid at least one newsgroup in standard list view: *alt.aol-sucks*.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL did list the newsgroup in the alternative description view, but changed the description to "Flames and complaints about America Online".
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] With AOL clients swarming Usenet newsgroups, the old, existing user base started to develop a strong distaste for both AOL and its clients, referring to the new state of affairs as Eternal September.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL discontinued access to Usenet on June 25, 2005.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] No official details were provided as to the cause of decommissioning Usenet access, except providing users the suggestion to access Usenet services from a third-party, Google Groups.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL then provided community-based message boards in lieu of Usenet.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL has a detailed set of guidelines and expectations for users on their service, known as the Terms of Service (TOS, also known as Conditions of Service (COS) in the UK).
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] It is separated into three different sections: *Member Agreement*, *Community Guidelines* and *Privacy Policy*.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] All three agreements are presented to users at time of registration and digital acceptance is achieved when they access the AOL service.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] During the period when volunteer chat room hosts and board monitors were used, chat room hosts were given a brief online training session and test on Terms of Service violations.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] There have been many complaints over rules that govern an AOL user's conduct.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Some users disagree with the TOS, citing the guidelines are too strict to follow coupled with the fact the TOS may change without users being made aware.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] A considerable cause for this was likely due to alleged censorship of user-generated content during the earlier years of growth for AOL.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] This decision drew fire from MoveOn, which characterized the program as an "email tax", and the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF), which characterized it as a shakedown of non-profits.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] A website called Dearaol.com was launched, with an online petition and a blog that garnered hundreds of signatures from people and organizations expressing their opposition to AOL's use of Goodmail.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Esther Dyson defended the move in an editorial in *The New York Times*, saying "I hope Goodmail succeeds, and that it has lots of competition.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] I also think it and its competitors will eventually transform into services that more directly serve the interests of mail recipients.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Tim Lee of the Technology Liberation Front posted an article that questioned the Electronic Frontier Foundation's adopting a confrontational posture when dealing with private companies.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] SpamAssassin developer Justin Mason posted some criticism of the EFF's and Moveon's "going overboard" in their opposition to the scheme.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] The dearaol.com campaign lost momentum and disappeared, with the last post to the now defunct dearaol.com blog—"AOL starts the shakedown" being made on May 9, 2006.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Comcast, who also used the service, announced on its website that Goodmail had ceased operations and as of February 4, 2011, they no longer used the service.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] On August 4, 2006, AOL released a compressed text file on one of its websites containing 20 million search keywords for over 650,000 users over a three-month period between March 1 and May 31, 2006, intended for research purposes.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL pulled the file from public access by August 7, but not before its wide distribution on the Internet by others.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Derivative research, titled *A Picture of Search*, was published by authors Pass, Chowdhury and Torgeson for The First International Conference on Scalable Information Systems.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] The data were used by websites such as AOLstalker for entertainment purposes, where users of AOLstalker are encouraged to judge AOL clients based on the humorousness of personal details revealed by search behavior.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] In 2003, Jason Smathers, an AOL employee, was convicted of stealing America Online's 92 million screen names and selling them to a known spammer.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Smathers pled guilty to conspiracy charges in 2005.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Smathers pled guilty to violations of the US CAN-SPAM Act of 2003.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] He was sentenced in August 2005 to 15 months in prison; the sentencing judge also recommended Smathers be forced to pay $84,000 in restitution, triple the $28,000 that he sold the addresses for.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] On February 27, 2012, a class action lawsuit was filed against Support.com, Inc. and partner AOL, Inc.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] The companies then offered to sell software—for which AOL allegedly charged $4.99 a month and Support.com $29—to remedy those problems.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Both AOL, Inc. and Support.com, Inc. settled on May 30, 2013, for $8.5 million.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] This included $25.00 to each valid class member and $100,000 each to Consumer Watchdog and the Electronic Frontier Foundation.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL continues to market Computer Checkup.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Following media reports about PRISM, NSA's massive electronic surveillance program, in June 2013, several technology companies were identified as participants, including AOL.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] According to leaks of said program, AOL joined the PRISM program in 2011.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] At one time, most AOL users had an online "profile" hosted by the AOL Hometown service.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] When AOL Hometown was discontinued, users had to create a new profile on Bebo.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] This was an unsuccessful attempt to create a social network that would compete with Facebook.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] When the value of Bebo decreased to a tiny fraction of the $850 million AOL paid for it, users were forced to recreate their profiles yet again, on a new service called AOL Lifestream.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] AOL decided to shut down Lifestream on February 24, 2017, and gave users one month's notice to save photos and videos that had been uploaded to Lifestream.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] Following the shutdown, AOL no longer provides any option for hosting user profiles.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] During the Hometown/Bebo/Lifestream era, another user's profile could be displayed by clicking the "Buddy Info" button in the AOL Desktop software.
[src:chicago-tribune/aol-p02] After the shutdown of Lifestream, this was no longer supported, but opened to the AIM home page (www.aim.com), which also became defunct, redirecting to AOL's home page.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The ***Chicago Tribune*** is an American daily newspaper based in Chicago, Illinois, United States.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Founded in 1847, it was formerly self-styled as the "World's Greatest Newspaper", a slogan from which its once-integrated WGN radio and WGN television received their call letters.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] It is the most-read daily newspaper in the Chicago metropolitan area and the Great Lakes region, and the sixth-largest newspaper by print circulation in the United States.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In the 1850s, under Joseph Medill, the *Chicago Tribune* became closely associated with the Illinois politician Abraham Lincoln, and the then new Republican Party's progressive wing.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In the 20th century, under Medill's grandson 'Colonel' Robert R.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] McCormick, its reputation was that of a crusading newspaper with an outlook that promoted American conservatism and opposed Franklin D.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Its reporting and commentary reached markets outside Chicago through family and corporate relationships at the New York *Daily News* and the *Washington Times-Herald*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Through much of the 20th century and into the early 21st, it employed a network of overseas news bureaus and foreign correspondents.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In the 1960s, its corporate parent owner, Tribune Company, began expanding into new markets by buying additional daily papers.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 2008, for the first time in its history, its editorial page endorsed a Democrat, Barack Obama, a U.S. senator from Illinois, for U.S. president.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Originally published solely as a broadsheet, the *Tribune* announced on January 13, 2009, that it would continue publishing as a broadsheet for home delivery, but it would publish in tabloid format for newsstand, news box, and commuter station sales.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The change, however, proved unpopular with readers; in August 2011, the *Tribune* discontinued the tabloid edition, returning to its established broadsheet format through all distribution channels.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* was owned by parent company Tribune Publishing.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In May 2021, Tribune Publishing was acquired by Alden Global Capital, which operates its media properties through Digital First Media; since then, the newspaper's coverage has evolved away from national and international news and toward coverage of Illinois and especially Chicago-area news.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* settled a lawsuit over illegal charges to consumers in 2013 and was sued again for deceptive billing practices in 2023.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* was founded by James Kelly, John E.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Forrest, publishing the first edition on June 10, 1847.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Numerous changes in ownership and editorship took place over the next eight years.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Initially, the *Tribune* was not politically affiliated, but it tended to support either the Whig or Free Soil parties against the Democrats in elections.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] By late 1853, it was frequently running editorials that criticized foreigners and Roman Catholics.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] About this time, it also became a strong proponent of the temperance movement.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] However nativist its editorials may have been, it was not until February 10, 1855, that the *Tribune* formally affiliated itself with the nativist American or Know Nothing party, whose candidate Levi Boone was elected Mayor of Chicago the following month.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Webster, later General Webster and chief of staff at the Battle of Shiloh, and Charles H.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Ray of Galena, Illinois, through Horace Greeley, convinced Joseph Medill of Cleveland's *Leader* to become managing editor.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Ray became editor-in-chief, Medill became the managing editor, and Alfred Cowles, Sr., brother of Edwin Cowles, initially was the bookkeeper.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Each purchased one third of the *Tribune*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Under their leadership, the *Tribune* distanced itself from the Know Nothings, and became the main Chicago organ of the Republican Party.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] However, the paper continued to print anti-Catholic and anti-Irish editorials, in the wake of the massive famine immigration from Ireland.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* absorbed three other Chicago publications under the new editors: the *Free West* in 1855, the *Democratic Press* of William Bross in 1858, and the *Chicago Democrat* in 1861, whose editor, John Wentworth, left his position when elected as Mayor of Chicago.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Between 1858 and 1860, the paper was known as the *Chicago Press & Tribune*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On October 25, 1860, it became the *Chicago Daily Tribune*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Before and during the American Civil War, the new editors strongly supported Abraham Lincoln, whom Medill helped secure the presidency in 1860, and pushed an abolitionist agenda.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The paper remained a force in Republican politics for years afterwards.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 1861, the *Tribune* published new lyrics by William W.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Patton for the song "John Brown's Body".
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] These rivaled the lyrics published two months later by Julia Ward Howe.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Medill served as mayor of Chicago for one term after the Great Chicago Fire of 1871.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In the 20th century, under Colonel Robert R.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] McCormick, who took control in the 1920s, the paper was strongly isolationist and aligned with the Old Right in its coverage of political news and social trends.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] It used the motto "The American Paper for Americans".
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] From the 1930s to the 1950s, it excoriated the Democrats and the New Deal of Franklin D.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Roosevelt, was resolutely disdainful of the British, and expressed support for Chiang Kai-shek and Sen.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] When McCormick assumed the position of co-editor with his cousin Joseph Medill Patterson in 1910, the *Tribune* was the third-best-selling paper among Chicago's eight dailies, with a circulation of only 188,000.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The young cousins added features such as advice columns and homegrown comic strips, such as *Little Orphan Annie* and *Moon Mullins*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] They promoted political crusades, and their first success came with the ouster of the Republican political boss of Illinois, Sen.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] At the same time, the *Tribune* competed with the Hearst paper, the *Chicago Examiner*, in a circulation war.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] By 1914, the cousins succeeded in forcing out James Keeley, the newspaper's managing editor.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] By 1918, the *Examiner* was forced to merge with the *Chicago Herald*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 1919, Patterson left the *Tribune* and moved to New York City to launch his own newspaper, the *New York Daily News*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In a renewed circulation war with Hearst's *Herald-Examiner*, McCormick and Hearst ran rival lotteries in 1922.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* won the battle, adding 250,000 readers to its ranks.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The same year, the *Chicago Tribune* hosted an international design competition for its new headquarters, the Tribune Tower, offering a $50,000 prize for first place.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The competition worked brilliantly as a publicity stunt, and more than 260 entries were received.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The winner was a neo-Gothic design by New York architects John Mead Howells and Raymond Hood.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Construction of the Tribune Tower was completed in 1925.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The newspaper sponsored a pioneering attempt at Arctic aviation in 1929, a proposed round-trip to Europe across Greenland and Iceland in a Sikorsky amphibious aircraft.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] However, the aircraft was destroyed by ice on July 15, 1929, near Ungava Bay at the tip of Labrador, Canada.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The crew were rescued by the Canadian science ship CSS *Acadia*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune*'s reputation for innovation extended to radio.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] It bought an early station, WDAP, in 1924 and renamed it WGN, the station call letters standing for the paper's self-description as the "World's Greatest Newspaper".
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] WGN Television was launched on April 5, 1948.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] These broadcast stations remained *Tribune* properties for nine decades and were among the oldest newspaper/broadcasting cross-ownerships in the country.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune*'s legendary sports editor Arch Ward created the Major League Baseball All-Star Game in 1933 as part of the city's Century of Progress exposition.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] One of the great scoops in *Tribune* history came when it obtained the text of the Treaty of Versailles in June 1919.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Another was its revelation of United States war plans on the eve of the Pearl Harbor attack.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune*'s June 7, 1942, front-page article implying that the United States had broken Japan's naval code could have resulted in the Japanese learning a closely guarded military secret.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The story implying that Americans broke the enemy naval codes was not cleared by censors, and had U.S.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Roosevelt so enraged that he considered shutting down the *Tribune*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] From 1940 to 1943, the paper supplemented its comic strip offerings with *The Chicago Tribune Comic Book*, responding to the new success of comic books.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] At the same time, it launched the more successful and longer-lasting *The Spirit Section*, which was also an attempt by newspapers to compete with the new medium.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Under McCormick's stewardship, the *Tribune* was a champion of modified spelling for simplicity.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Beginning in 1934, the paper compiled lists of dozens of common words whose spelling could be made "saner", removing double L's and shortening "-ogue" endings to "-og", among other changes.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The paper is known for a mistake it made during the 1948 presidential election.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] At that time, much of its composing room staff was on strike.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Early returns led editors to believe (along with many in the country) that the Republican candidate Thomas Dewey would win.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] An early edition of the next day's paper carried the headline "Dewey Defeats Truman", turning the paper into a collector's item.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Truman won and proudly brandished the newspaper in a famous picture taken at St.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Beneath the headline was a false article, written by Arthur Sears Henning, which purported to describe West Coast results although written before East Coast election returns were available.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] McCormick, a vigorous campaigner for the Republican Party, died in 1955, just four days before Democratic boss Richard J.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Daley was elected mayor for the first time.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 1969, under the leadership of publisher Harold Grumhaus and editor Clayton Kirkpatrick, the *Tribune* began reporting from a wider viewpoint.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The paper retained its Republican and conservative perspective in its editorials, but it began to publish perspectives in wider commentary that represented a spectrum of diverse opinions, while its news reporting no longer had the conservative slant it had in the McCormick years.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In January 1974, *Time* magazine named the *Tribune* on its "Ten Best American Dailies" list for its local investigative reporting under George Bliss as well as its "calmer tone and a less polemical approach to events" brought on by Kirkpatrick.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On May 1, 1974, in a major feat of journalism, the *Tribune* published the complete 246,000-word text of the Watergate tapes, in a 44-page supplement that hit the streets 24 hours after the transcripts' release by the Nixon White House.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Not only was the *Tribune* the first newspaper to publish the transcripts, but it beat the U.S.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Government Printing Office's published version, and made headlines doing so.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Nixon has upheld the standards and dignity of the Presidency," and called for Nixon's resignation.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* call for Nixon to resign made news, reflecting not only the change in the type of conservatism practiced by the paper, but as a watershed event in terms of Nixon's hopes for survival in office.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The White House reportedly perceived the *Tribune*'s editorial as a loss of a longtime supporter and as a blow to Nixon's hopes to weather the scandal.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On December 7, 1975, Kirkpatrick announced in a column on the editorial page that Rick Soll, a "young and talented columnist" for the paper, whose work had "won a following among many *Tribune* readers over the last two years", had resigned from the paper.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] He had acknowledged that one column he wrote, dating to November 23, 1975, contained verbatim passages written by another columnist in 1967 and later published in a collection.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Kirkpatrick did not identify the columnist.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The passages in question, Kirkpatrick wrote, were from a notebook where Soll regularly entered words, phrases and bits of conversation which he had wished to remember.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The paper initially suspended Soll for a month without pay.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Kirkpatrick wrote that further evidence was revealed came out that another of Soll's columns contained information which he knew was false.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] At that point, *Tribune* editors decided to accept the resignation offered by Soll when the internal investigation began.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] After leaving, Soll married Pam Zekman, a Chicago newspaper (and future TV) reporter.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] He worked for the short-lived *Chicago Times* magazine, by Small Newspaper Group Inc. of Kankakee, Illinois, in the late 1980s.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Soll was born in 1946, in Chicago, to Marjorie and Jules Soll.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Soll graduated from New Trier High School, received a Bachelor of Arts in 1968 from Colgate University, and a master's degree from Medill School of Journalism, Northwestern University in 1970.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In January 1977, *Tribune* columnist Will Leonard died at age 64.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In March 1978, the *Tribune* announced that it hired columnist Bob Greene from the *Chicago Sun-Times*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Kirkpatrick stepped down as editor in 1979 and was succeeded by Maxwell McCrohon, who served as editor until 1981.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] He was transitioned to a corporate position.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] McCrohon held the corporate position until 1983, when he left to become editor-in-chief of the United Press International.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] James Squires served as the paper's editor from July 1981 until December 1989.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Jack Fuller served as the *Tribune*'s editor from 1989 until 1993, when he became the president and chief executive officer of the *Chicago Tribune*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Howard Tyner served as the *Tribune*'s editor from 1993 until 2001, when he was promoted to vice president/editorial for Tribune Publishing.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* won 11 Pulitzer prizes during the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Editorial cartoonist Dick Locher won the award in 1983, and editorial cartoonist Jeff MacNelly won one in 1985.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Then, future editor Jack Fuller won a Pulitzer for editorial writing in 1986.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 1987, reporters Jeff Lyon and Peter Gorner won a Pulitzer for explanatory reporting, and in 1988, Dean Baquet, William Gaines and Ann Marie Lipinski won a Pulitzer for investigative reporting.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 1989, Lois Wille won a Pulitzer for editorial writing and Clarence Page snagged the award for commentary.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 1994, Ron Kotulak won a Pulitzer for explanatory journalism, while R.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Bruce Dold won it for editorial writing.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 1998, reporter Paul Salopek won a Pulitzer for explanatory writing, and in 1999, architecture critic Blair Kamin won it for criticism.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In September 1981, baseball writer Jerome Holtzman was hired by the *Tribune* after a 38-year career at the *Sun-Times*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In September 1982, the *Chicago Tribune* opened a new $180 million printing facility, Freedom Center.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In November 1982, *Tribune* managing editor William H.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] "Bill" Jones, who had won a Pulitzer Prize in 1971, died at age 43 of cardiac arrest as a result of complications from a long battle with leukemia.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In May 1983, *Tribune* columnist Aaron Gold died at age 45 of complications from leukemia.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Gold had coauthored the Tribune's "Inc." column with Michael Sneed and prior to that had written the paper's "Tower Ticker" column.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* scored a coup in 1984 when it hired popular columnist Mike Royko away from the rival *Sun-Times*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] "He has done a great job for us," editor James Squires said at the time.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] "It's a question of how much a person can do physically.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] We think you need to be a newspaper person first, and Gene Siskel has always tried to do that.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] But there comes a point when a career is so big that you can't do that." Siskel declined to comment on the new arrangement, but Ebert publicly criticized Siskel's *Tribune* bosses for punishing Siskel for taking their television program to a company other than Tribune Entertainment.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Siskel remained in that freelance position until he died in 1999.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] He was replaced as film critic by Dave Kehr.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In August 1988, *Chicago Tribune* reporter Michael Coakley died at age 41 of complications from AIDS.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In November 1992, *Tribune* associate subject editor Searle "Ed" Hawley was arrested by Chicago police and charged with seven counts of aggravated criminal sexual abuse for allegedly having sex with three juveniles in his home in Evanston, Illinois.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Hawley formally resigned from the paper in early 1993, and pleaded guilty in April 1993.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In October 1993, the *Tribune* fired its longtime military affairs writer, retired Marine David Evans, saying publicly that the position was being replaced by a national security writer.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In December 1993, the *Tribune*'s longtime Washington, D.C. bureau chief, Nicholas Horrock, was fired after he chose not to attend a meeting that editor Howard Tyner requested of him in Chicago.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Horrock, who shortly thereafter left the paper, was replaced by James Warren, who attracted new attention to the *Tribune*'s D.C. bureau through his continued attacks on celebrity broadcast journalists in Washington.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In December 1993, the *Tribune* hired Margaret Holt from the *South Florida Sun-Sentinel* as its assistant managing editor for sports, making her the first female to head a sports department at any of the nation's 10 largest newspapers.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In mid-1995, Holt was replaced as sports editor by Tim Franklin and shifted to a newly created job, customer service editor.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 1994, reporter Brenda You was fired by the *Tribune* after free-lancing for supermarket tabloid newspapers and lending them photographs from the *Tribune*'s photo library.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] She later worked for the *National Enquirer* and as a producer for *The Jerry Springer Show* before committing suicide in November 2005.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In April 1994, the *Tribune*'s new television critic, Ken Parish Perkins, wrote an article about then-WFLD morning news anchor Bob Sirott in which Perkins quoted Sirott as making a statement that Sirott later denied making.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Sirott criticized Perkins on the air, and the *Tribune* later printed a correction acknowledging that Sirott had never made that statement.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Eight months later, Perkins stepped down as TV critic, and he left the paper shortly thereafter.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The program brought young journalists in and out of the paper for one-year stints, seldom resulting in a full-time job.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Hill, who wrote for the paper from 1992 until 1993, acknowledged to the *Chicago Reader* that she had written the diatribe originally for the Internet, and that the piece eventually was edited for *Newcity*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 1997, the *Tribune* celebrated its 150th anniversary in part by tapping longtime reporter Stevenson Swanson to edit the book *Chicago Days: 150 Defining Moments in the Life of a Great City*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On April 29, 1997, popular columnist Mike Royko died of a brain aneurysm.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On September 2, 1997, the *Tribune* promoted longtime City Hall reporter John Kass to take Royko's place as the paper's principal Page Two news columnist.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On June 1, 1997, the *Tribune* published what ended up becoming a very popular column by Mary Schmich called "Advice, like youth, probably just wasted on the young", otherwise known as "Wear Sunscreen" or the "Sunscreen Speech".
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The most popular and well-known form of the essay is the successful music single released in 1999, accredited to Baz Luhrmann.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 1998, reporter Jerry Thomas was fired by the *Tribune* after he wrote a cover article on boxing promoter Don King for *Emerge* magazine at the same time that he was writing a cover article on King for the *Chicago Tribune* Sunday magazine.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The paper decided to fire Thomas—and suspend his photographer on the *Emerge* story, Pulitzer Prize-winning *Tribune* photographer Ovie Carter for a month—because Thomas did not tell the *Tribune* about his outside work and also because the *Emerge* story wound up appearing in print first.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* has been a leader on the Internet, acquiring 10 percent of America Online in the early 1990s, then launching such web sites as Chicagotribune.com (1995), Metromix.com (1996), **ChicagoSports.com** (1999), **ChicagoBreakingNews.com** (2008), and ChicagoNow (2009).
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 2002, the paper launched a tabloid edition targeted at 18- to 34-year-olds known as *RedEye*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Ann Marie Lipinski was the paper's editor from February 2001 until stepping down on July 17, 2008.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Kern was named the paper's editor in July 2008.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In early August 2008, managing editor for news Hanke Gratteau resigned, and several weeks later, managing editor for features James Warren resigned as well.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Both were replaced by Jane Hirt, who previously had been the editor of the *Tribune*'s *RedEye* tabloid.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In June 2000, Times Mirror merged with Tribune Company making *The Baltimore Sun* and its community papers Baltimore Sun Media Group / Patuxent Publishing a subsidiary of Tribune.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In July 2000, Tribune outdoors columnist John Husar, who had written about his need for a new liver transplant, died at age 63, just over a week after receiving part of a new liver from a live donor.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Howard County Times* was named 2010 Newspaper of the Year by the Suburban Newspaper Association.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Towson Times* expands coverage beyond the Towson area and includes Baltimore County government and politics.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* won five Pulitzer prizes in the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 2003, editorial writer Cornelia Grumman snagged the award for editorial writing.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 2005, Julia Keller won a Pulitzer for feature reporting on a tornado that struck Utica, Illinois.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] And, in 2008, an investigative reporting team including Patricia Callahan, Maurice Possley, Sam Roe, Ted Gregory, Michael Oneal, Evan Osnos and photojournalist Scott Strazzante won the Pulitzer for its series about faulty government regulation of defective toys, cribs and car seats.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In late 2001, sports columnist Michael Holley announced he was leaving the *Tribune* after just two months because he was homesick.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] He ultimately returned to *The Boston Globe*, where he had been working immediately before the *Tribune* had hired him.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] "Greene's behavior was a serious violation of *Tribune* ethics and standards for its journalists," Lipinski wrote.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In January 2003, Mike Downey, formerly of the *Los Angeles Times*, was hired as new *Tribune* sports columnist.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] He and colleague Rick Morrissey would write the *In the Wake of the News Column* originated by Ring Lardner.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In March 2004, the *Tribune* announced that freelance reporter Uli Schmetzer, who retired from the *Tribune* in 2002 after 16 years as a foreign correspondent, had fabricated the name and occupation of a person he had quoted in a story.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The paper terminated Schmetzer as a contract reporter and began a review of the 300 stories that Schmetzer had written over the prior three years.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] "Upon questioning, the freelance writer indicated the column was based on an amalgam of three restaurants and could not verify the prices," the paper noted.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] After the correction, the *Tribune* stopped using Falanga.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In October 2004, *Tribune* editor Ann Marie Lipinski at the last minute spiked a story written for the paper's WomanNews section by freelance reporter Lisa Bertagnoli titled "You c_nt say that (or can you?)," about a noted vulgarism.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The paper ordered every spare body to go to the *Tribune*'s printing plant to pull already-printed WomanNews sections containing the story from the October 27 package of preprinted sections in the *Tribune*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In September 2008, the *Tribune* considered hiring controversial sports columnist Jay Mariotti, shortly after his abrupt resignation from *Tribune* archrival *Chicago Sun-Times*.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Discussions ultimately ended, however, after the *Sun-Times* threatened to sue for violating Mariotti's noncompete agreement, which was to run until August 2009.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Sports columnist Rick Morrissey defected to the *Sun-Times* in December 2009.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Reporters declined to speak on the record to the Associated Press about their issues.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] "We'll let the e-mail speak for itself," reporter John Chase told the AP.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In the wake of the controversy, Kern abruptly discontinued the effort, which he described as "a brief market research project".
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* broke the story on May 29, 2009, that several students had been admitted to the University of Illinois based upon connections or recommendations by the school's Board of Trustees, Chicago politicians, and members of the Rod Blagojevich administration.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Initially denying the existence of a so-called "Category I" admissions program, university President B.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Joseph "Joe" White and Chancellor Richard Herman later admitted that there were instances of preferential treatment.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Although they claimed the list was short and their role was minor, the *Tribune*, in particular, revealed emails through a FOIA finding that White had received a recommendation for a relative of convicted fundraiser Tony Rezko to be admitted.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The Tribune also later posted emails from Herman pushing for underqualified students to be accepted.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* has since filed suit against the university administration under the Freedom of Information Act to acquire the names of students benefited by administrative clout and impropriety.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On February 8, 2010, the *Chicago Tribune* shrank its newspaper's width by an inch.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] They said that the new format was becoming the industry standard and that there would be minimal content changes.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In July 2011, the *Chicago Tribune* underwent its first round of layoffs of editorial employees in more than two years, letting go about 20 editors and reporters.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Among those let go were DuPage County reporter Art Barnum, Editorial Board member Pat Widder and photographer Dave Pierini.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On March 15, 2012, the *Tribune* laid off 15 editorial staffers, including security guard Wendell Smothers (Smothers then died on November 12, 2012).
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] At the same time, the paper gave buyouts to six editorial staffers, including Pulitzer Prize-winning reporter William Mullen, Barbara Mahany and Nancy Reese.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In June 2012, the *Tribune*'s Pulitzer Prize-winning cultural critic Julia Keller left the paper to join the faculty of Ohio University and to pursue a career as a novelist.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In October 2012, the *Tribune*'s science and medicine reporter, Trine Tsouderos, quit to join a public relations firm.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Also in October 2012, the *Tribune* announced plans to create a paywall for its website, offering digital-only subscriptions at $14.99 per month, starting on November 1, 2012.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Seven-day print subscribers would continue to have unlimited online access at no additional charge.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In February 2013, the *Tribune* agreed to pay a total of $660,000 to settle a class-action lawsuit that had been filed against the paper by 46 current and former reporters of its TribLocal local-news reporting group over unpaid overtime wages.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The suit had been filed in federal court on behalf of Carolyn Rusin, who had been a TribLocal staff reporter from July 2010 until October 2011.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The paper's TribLocal unit had been formed in 2007 and uses staff reporters, freelance writers and user-generated content to produce hyperlocal Chicago-area community news.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On June 12, 2013, the Boston Marathon bombing tribute was posted again, which showed the words "We are Chicago" above the names of Boston sports teams.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On the graphic on June 12, the word "Bruins" was ripped off and the comment was added, "Yeah, not right now we're not", in a reference to the 2013 Stanley Cup Finals, which play the Chicago Blackhawks against the Boston Bruins.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Gerould Kern tweeted later that the *Tribune* "still supports [Boston] after all you've been through.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On November 20, 2013, the *Tribune* laid off another 12 or so editorial staffers.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On April 6, 2014, the *Tribune* increased the newsstand price of its Sunday/Thanksgiving Day paper by 50 percent to $2.99 for a single copy.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] By January 2017 the price increased again, up $1 or 40% at newsracks, to $3.50.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On January 28, 2015, metropolitan editor Peter Kendall was named managing editor, replacing Jane Hirt, who had resigned several months earlier.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Colin McMahon was named associate editor.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On February 18, 2016, the Tribune announced the retirement of editor Gerould Kern and the immediate promotion of the paper's editorial page editor, R.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On June 9, 2018, the Tribune ended their 93-year stint at Tribune Tower and moved to One Prudential Plaza.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The tower was later converted to condos.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On February 27, 2020, the *Tribune* announced that publisher and editor Bruce Dold would leave the *Tribune* on April 30, 2020, and would step down immediately as editor in chief.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] His replacement as editor was Colin McMahon.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Also, the paper announced that one of the two managing editors of the paper, Peter Kendall, would leave the *Tribune* on February 28, 2020.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In January 2021, the *Chicago Tribune* moved out of One Prudential Plaza, and relocated their offices and newsroom to Freedom Center.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In May 2021, the paper was purchased by Alden Global Capital.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Alden immediately launched a round of employee buyouts, reducing the newsroom staff by 25 percent, and the cuts continued.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] A former reporter said the paper is being "snuffed out, quarter after quarter after quarter".
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Mitch Pugh was named the *Tribune*'s executive editor on August 20, 2021, after eight years in the same role at *The Post and Courier* in Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* has remained economically conservative, being widely skeptical of increasing the minimum wage and entitlement spending.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 2018, the *Chicago Tribune* and *Los Angeles Times* withdrew their websites from European Union nations to avoid the purview of the General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 2004, the *Tribune* endorsed President George W.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Bush for reelection, a decision consistent with its longstanding support for the Republican Party.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 2008, it endorsed Democratic candidate and Illinois junior U.S.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Senator Barack Obama—the first time that it had ever endorsed a Democrat for president.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* endorsed Obama once again for reelection in 2012, and in 2020 would endorse another Democrat, Joe Biden, who had served as vice president under Obama.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* has occasionally backed candidates of other parties for president.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 1872, it supported Horace Greeley, a former Republican Party newspaper editor, and in 1912 the paper endorsed Theodore Roosevelt, who ran on the Progressive Party slate against Republican President William Howard Taft.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 2016, the Tribune endorsed the Libertarian Party candidate, former New Mexico Governor Gary Johnson, for president, over Republican Donald Trump and Democrat Hillary Clinton.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Even when it uniformly backed Republicans for president, the *Tribune* endorsed some Democrats for lesser offices, including endorsements of Bill Foster, Barack Obama for the Senate and Democrat Melissa Bean, who defeated Philip Crane, the House of Representatives' longest-serving Republican.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Although the *Tribune* endorsed George Ryan in the 1998 Illinois gubernatorial race, the paper subsequently investigated and reported on the scandals surrounding Ryan during his preceding years as Secretary of State.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Ryan declined to run for re-election in 2002 and was subsequently indicted, convicted and imprisoned as a result of the scandal.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Chicago Tribune* was the founding business unit of Tribune Company (since renamed *Tribune Media*), which included many newspapers and television stations around the country.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In Chicago, Tribune Media owned the WGN radio station (720 AM) and WGN-TV (Channel 9).
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Tribune Company also owned the *Los Angeles Times*—which displaced the Tribune as the company's largest property—and the Chicago Cubs baseball team.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The Cubs were sold in 2009;the newspapers spun off in 2014 as Tribune Publishing.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Tribune Company owned the New York *Daily News* from its 1919 founding until its 1991 sale to British newspaper magnate Robert Maxwell.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Joseph Medill Patterson — was a grandson of Joseph Medill and a cousin of *Tribune* editor Robert McCormick.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Both Patterson and McCormick were enthusiasts of simplified spelling, another hallmark of their papers for many years.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In 2008, the Tribune Company sold the Long Island newspaper *Newsday*—founded in 1940 by Patterson's daughter (and Medill's great-granddaughter), Alicia Patterson—to Long Island cable TV company Cablevision.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] From 1925 to 2018, the Chicago Tribune was housed in the Tribune Tower on North Michigan Avenue on the Magnificent Mile.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The building is neo-Gothic in style, and the design was the winner of an international competition hosted by the Tribune.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The Chicago Tribune moved in June 2018 to the Prudential Plaza office complex overlooking Millennium Park after Tribune Media sold Tribune Tower to developers.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Colonel McCormick prevented the *Tribune* for years from participating in the Pulitzer Prize competition.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] But it has won 29 of the awards over the years, including many for editorial writing.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* won its first post-McCormick Pulitzer in 1961, when Carey Orr won the award for editorial cartooning.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Reporter George Bliss won a Pulitzer the following year for reporting, and reporter Bill Jones another in 1971 for reporting.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] A reporting team won the award in 1973, followed by reporter William Mullen and photographer Ovie Carter, who won a Pulitzer for international reporting in 1975.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] A local reporting team won the award in 1976, and architecture critic Paul Gapp won a Pulitzer in 1979.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* won the Pulitzer Prize for local reporting on May 4, 2026, for its coverage of Operation Midway Blitz, the Trump administration's immigration enforcement mission in the Chicago area last fall.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In December 2007, the Tribune Company was bought out by Chicago real estate magnate Sam Zell in an $8.2 billion deal.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] A year after going private, following a $124 million third-quarter loss, the Tribune Company filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection on December 8, 2008.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The company made its filing with the U.S.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Bankruptcy Court for the District of Delaware, citing a debt of $13 billion and assets of $7.6 billion.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Sam Zell originally planned to turn the company into a private company through the creation of an ESOP (employee stock ownership plan) within the company, but due to poor management that existed prior to his ownership, this did not work out as well as he intended.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] As part of its bankruptcy plan, owner Sam Zell intended to sell the Cubs to reduce debt.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] This sale has become linked to the corruption charges leading to the arrest of former Illinois Governor Rod Blagojevich on December 9, 2008.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Specifically, Blagojevich was accused of exploiting the paper's financial trouble in an effort to have several editors fired.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] In the bankruptcy, unsecured bondholders of Tribune Co. essentially claimed that ordinary Tribune shareholders participated in a "fraudulent transfer" of wealth.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The law firm Brown Rudnick, representing the Aurelius group of junior creditors, filed fraudulent transfer claims and fraud claims against 33,000 to 35,000 stockholders who bought Tribune stock.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Prolonged due to these claims against former officers, directors, and every former stockholder of the Chicago Tribune Company, the Tribune's bankruptcy-related legal and professional fees of $500 million were more than twice the usual amount for that size of company.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The Tribune Co. emerged from bankruptcy in January 2013, partially owned by private equity firms which had speculated on its distressed debt.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The reorganized company's plan included selling off many of its assets.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Tribune Publishing, owning the *Chicago Tribune*, *Los Angeles Times*, and eight other newspapers, was spun off as a separate publicly traded company in August 2014.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The parent Tribune Company was renamed Tribune Media.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Tribune Publishing started life with a $350 million loan, $275 million of which was paid as a dividend to Tribune Media.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The publishing company was also due to lease its office space from Tribune Media for $30 million per year through 2017.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Spinning off Tribune Publishing avoided the capital gains taxes that would accrue from selling those assets.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The shares in Tribune Publishing were given tax-free to stakeholders in Tribune Media, the largest shareholder was Oaktree Capital Management with 18.5%.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] Tribune Media, retaining the non-newspaper broadcasting, entertainment, real estate, and other investments, also sold off some of the non-newspaper properties.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] On February 7, 2018, Tribune Publishing Company agreed to sell the *Los Angeles Times* to billionaire biotech investor Patrick Soon-Shiong.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The purchase, made through Soon-Shiong's Nant Capital investment fund, was valued at $500 million, along with the assumption of $90 million in pension liabilities.
[src:chicago-tribune/chicago-tribune] The deal, which also included the *San Diego Union-Tribune* and other assets, was finalized on June 16, 2018.
